 An Annotated Guide to Royal Canadian Mounted Police in Print and Performance|publisher=Scarecrow Press|isbn=9780810823303}}\n* {{cite book|last=Dawson|first=Michael|year=1998|title=The Mountie from Dime Novel to Disney|publisher=Between The Lines|isbn=9781896357164}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Strange|first1=Carolyn|last2=Loo|first2=Tina Merrill|year=2004|title=True Crime, True North: The Golden Age of Canadian Pulp Magazines|publisher=Raincoast Books|isbn=9781551926896}}\n* {{cite book|first1=Scott|last1=MacKenzie|first2=Anna|last2=Westerst\u00e5hl Stenport|year=2015|title=Films on Ice: Cinemas of the Arctic|publisher=Edinburgh University Press|isbn=9780748694174}}\n* {{cite journal|title='Nothing But Hill and Hollow': The Canadian Border as American Frontier in the Hollywood Northern|journal=Comparative American Studies|volume=13|issue=1\u20132|pages=107\u2013121|first=Richard G.|last=Baker|date=24 Jun 2015|doi=10.1179/1477570015Z.000000000102}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.pulpanddagger.com/pulpmag/editorial11.html \"Looking for Dudley Do-Right\"] at [http://www.pulpanddagger.com/pulpmag/contents.html Pulp and Dagger Fiction]\n* [http://www.pulpanddagger.com/pulpmag/editorial14.html Northern Romances Editorial] at [http://www.pulpanddagger.com/pulpmag/contents.html Pulp and Dagger Fiction]\n* [http://www.canuxploitation.com/article/mountie.html \"Romancing the Redcoat: A Canadian Hero Lost in Hollywood\"] at [http://www.canuxploitation.com Canuxploitation]\n* [http://www.museevirtuel.ca/Exhibitions/Police/eng_html/7.3_legacy_popculture.html The RCMP in Popular Culture]\n* [http://www.b-westerns.com/mounties.htm The Mountie Films at B-Westerns]\n* [http://www.mounted-police.00server.com NORTH WEST MOUNTED POLICE Canadian Mounties in Literature]\n* [http://particle.physics.ucdavis.edu/Places/Canada/CanadaMovies.html Hollywood's View of Canada] (list of films)\n* [http://www.virtualmuseum.ca/Exhibitions/Force/en/myths/ The Force in the North - Myths at Virtual Museum Canada]\n\n{{Film genres}}\n\n[[Category:Fiction by genre]]\n[[Category:Film genres]]\n[[Category:Western (genre)]]\n[[Category:Royal Canadian Mounted Police in fiction]]\n[[Category:Yukon in fiction]]\n[[Category:Northern films| ]]\n[[Category:Cinema of Canada]]\n[[Category:Canadian folklore]]\n[[Category:Klondike Gold Rush in fiction]]\n[[Category:Northwest Territories in fiction]]\n", "name_user": "2a02:c7f:8651:3300:683b:de4a:4ab3:b444", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eExamples of Northerns)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Northern_(genre)"}
{"title_page": "The Catcher in the Rye in popular culture", "text_new": "{{More citations needed|date=May 2012}}\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:''The Catcher in the Rye'' in popular culture}}\nThe 1951 novel '''''[[The Catcher in the Rye]]''''' by [[J. D. Salinger]] has had a lasting influence<ref name=\"WP\">{{cite news\n| url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A43680-2004Oct18.html\n| title = J.D. Salinger's Holden Caulfield, Aging Gracelessly\n| author = Jonathan Yardley\n| work = [[The Washington Post]]\n| date = 2004-10-19\n| accessdate = 2007-05-21\n| quote = \"The Catcher in the Rye\" is a maladroit, mawkish novel, but there can be no question about its popularity or influence.\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n| url = http://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=FB0C17FD345912738DDDAC0894D9405B848AF1D3\n| title = Brooklyn College\n| author = Barry Roth\n| work = [[The New York Times]]\n| date = 1964-01-05\n| accessdate = 2007-05-21\n| quote = ...the \"do you think you'll ever feel about me the way you used to feel about 'Catcher in the Rye'?\" influence of the theater and movies often stimulates collegians to read these and other writers.\n}}</ref> as it remains both a [[bestseller]]<ref name=\"Guinn\" /> and a [[List of most commonly challenged books in the U.S.|frequently challenged book]].<ref name=\"Guinn\">{{cite news\n| url = http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=ET&p_theme=et&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EDCAD301800C85B&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D\n| title = 'Catcher in the Rye' still influences 50 years later\n| author = Jeff Guinn\n| work = [[Erie Times-News]]\n| date = 2001-08-10\n| accessdate = 2007-12-18\n| format = fee required\n}} [http://www.accessmylibrary.com/coms2/summary_0286-6739335_ITM Alternate URL].</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.ala.org/ala/oif/bannedbooksweek/bbwlinks/100mostfrequently.htm\n |title=100 Most Frequently Challenged Books of 1990\u20132000\n |publisher=[[American Library Association]]\n |accessdate=2007-01-21\n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070118015806/http://www.ala.org/ala/oif/bannedbooksweek/bbwlinks/100mostfrequently.htm\n |archivedate=2007-01-18\n |url-status=dead\n}}</ref> Numerous works in [[popular culture]] have referenced the novel.<ref name=\"SB\">{{cite news\n| url = http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=SB&p_theme=sb&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EC831DF2A54202C&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D\n| title = 'Rye' misfit's rugged spirit inspires works\n| work = [[The Sacramento Bee]]\n| date = 2001-06-07\n| accessdate = 2007-05-21\n| format = fee required\n| quote = \"The Catcher in the Rye\" has influenced the work of many writers, filmmakers and musicians. Here's a look at some of the more notable entries...\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n| url = http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=WO&p_theme=wo&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EB9EAB0A95F7BFF&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D\n| title = Sixties to Howl Once Again in College Literature Course\n| work = [[Telegram & Gazette]]\n| date = 2001-04-08\n| accessdate = 2007-05-21\n| format = fee required\n| quote = Mr. Patterson explained his inclusion of a 1952 novel in his \"Literature of the 1960s\" course this way: \"I kept seeing references to Holden Caulfield...\n}}</ref>\nFactors contributing to the novel's mystique and impact include its portrayal of protagonist [[Holden Caulfield]];<ref name=\"WP\" /> its tone of sincerity;<ref name=\"WP\" /> its themes of familial neglect,<ref name=\"SFGate\" /> tension between teens and society,<ref name=\"Guinn\" /><ref name=\"SFGate\" /> and rebellion;<ref name=\"SFGate\" /> its previous banned status;<ref>{{cite news\n| url = http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=HT&p_theme=ht&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EAFEA3BF023F923&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D\n| title = Banned Books Offer Classic Opportunities\n| work = [[Sarasota Herald-Tribune]]\n| date = 1996-10-23\n| accessdate = 2007-05-21\n| format = fee required\n| quote = [...] one of the controversial books that has been censored in the past is J.D. Salinger's ``The Catcher in the Rye.' [...] all through his life he'd hear references to Holden Caulfield and his crazy red hunting hat, and if he wanted to understand those references, [...]\n}}</ref> and Salinger's reclusiveness.<ref name=\"WP\" />\n\n''The Catcher in the Rye'' has inspired \"rewrites\" which have been said to form their own genre.<ref name=\"Menand\">{{cite news\n| title = Holden at fifty\n| author = [[Louis Menand]]\n| work = [[The New Yorker]]\n| date = 2001-09-27\n}}</ref>\nOn the other hand, there are examples of similarities between the novel and other works that were not intended by their authors,<ref name=\"SFGate\" /><ref>{{cite news\n |url         = http://www.dailyprincetonian.com/archives/2005/11/09/news/13716.shtml\n |title       = Novelist Sittenfeld chronicles 'Prep' life\n |author      = Joy Karugu\n |work        = [[The Daily Princetonian]]\n |date        = 2005-11-09\n |accessdate  = 2007-12-19\n |quote       = That's an easy comparison people often make \u2014 because of its setting and general topic.\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20081002030516/http://www.dailyprincetonian.com/archives/2005/11/09/news/13716.shtml\n |archivedate = 2008-10-02\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n| url = https://www.nytimes.com/2007/09/23/books/review/Peck-t.html?pagewanted=print\n| title = \u2018The Outsiders\u2019: 40 Years Later\n| author = Dale Peck\n| work = [[New York Times]]\n| date = 2007-09-23\n| accessdate = 2007-12-19\n| quote = ...it\u2019s likely that Hinton\u2019s echo of the testimonial frame Salinger used in \u201cThe Catcher in the Rye\u201d (\u201cIf you really want to hear about it\u201d) wasn\u2019t consciously intended...\n}}</ref> which suggests that the novel is \"present, at least spiritually, in ... any story line that involves quirky young people struggling to find their places in a society prone to reward conformity and condemn individuality.\"<ref name=\"Guinn\" />\n\nWhile the novel is linked to several murders and murder attempts, it has been claimed that the novel's overall effect on society is \"far more positive than negative.\"<ref name=\"Guinn\" />\n\nThe novel also helped popularize the slang verb \"screw up\".<ref>{{cite news\n| url = https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9C0CE2DF1138F93BA35757C0A966958260&sec=&spon=&pagewanted=2\n| title = Screwing Up\n| author = William Safire\n| work = [[The New York Times]]\n| date = 1990-04-08\n| accessdate = 2007-12-20\n| pages = 2\n| quote = Screw up, in this sense, is first found in a December 1942 issue of Yank, and was further popularized in the 1951 ''Catcher in the Rye,'' the famed novel by J. D. Salinger: ''Boy, it really screws up my sex life something awful.''\n}}</ref>\n\nIn recent years{{when|date=March 2019}} there has been a discussion of depression as exhibited in Holden Caulfield.<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Depression in J.D. Salinger's The Catcher in the Rye\n| editor = Dedria Bryfonski\n| work = [[Greenhaven Press]]\n| date = 2009\n}}</ref>\n\n==Shootings==\nThe best-known event associated with ''The Catcher in the Rye'' is arguably [[Mark David Chapman]]'s [[Murder of John Lennon|shooting of John Lennon]].<ref>{{cite news\n| url = https://www.usatoday.com/news/index/colo/colo22.htm\n| title = Kids, online and off, feast on violence\n|author1=Leslie Miller |author2=Susan Wlosczyczna |author3=Joh Chetwynd |author4=Gary Levin |author5=Claudia Puig |author6=Mike Snider |author7=Kevin V. Johnson | work = [[USA Today]]\n| date = 1999-04-22\n| accessdate = 2007-05-21\n| quote = [[Lindsay Doran]], president of [[United Artists]], says, \"[...] You can't not like ''Catcher in the Rye'' because someone read it and killed John Lennon.\"\n}}</ref>\nChapman identified with the novel's narrator to the extent that he wanted to change his name to Holden Caulfield. On the night he shot Lennon, Chapman was found with a copy of the book in which he had written \"<u>This</u> is my statement\" and signed Holden's name.<ref name=\"Salon\">{{cite web\n |url         = http://dir.salon.com/story/books/feature/2003/12/15/books_kill/index1.html\n |title       = When books kill\n |author      = Aidan Doyle\n |publisher   = [[Salon.com]]\n |date        = 2003-12-15\n |accessdate  = 2007-05-21\n |pages       = 2\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20071105025510/http://dir.salon.com/story/books/feature/2003/12/15/books_kill/index1.html\n |archivedate = 2007-11-05\n}}</ref> Later, he read a passage from the novel to address the court during his sentencing.<ref name=\"Whitfield, 571\u2013572\">Whitfield, 571\u2013572.</ref> [[Daniel Stashower]] speculated that Chapman had wanted Lennon's innocence to be preserved by death, inspired by Holden's wish to preserve children's innocence despite Holden's later realization that children should be left alone.<ref name=\"Whitfield, 571\u2013572\"/>\n\nAfter [[John Hinckley, Jr.]]'s [[Reagan assassination attempt|assassination attempt]] on [[Ronald Reagan]] in 1981, police found ''The Catcher in the Rye'' among half a dozen other books in his hotel room.<ref>Whitfield, 572.</ref>\n\n[[Robert John Bardo]], who murdered [[Rebecca Schaeffer]], was carrying the book when he visited Schaeffer's apartment in Hollywood on July 18, 1989 and murdered her.<ref>\n{{cite web\n| url = http://www.amarillo.com/stories/091000/boo_tellingondad.shtml\n| title = Telling on Dad\n| author = Linton Weeks\n| publisher = [[Amarillo Globe-News]]\n| date = 2000-09-10\n| accessdate = 2009-01-13\n| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110604005125/http://amarillo.com/stories/091000/boo_tellingondad.shtml\n| archive-date = 2011-06-04\n| url-status = dead\n}}\n</ref>\n\n[[Peter Falconio]] was reported to be reading the novel prior to  his disappearance from the Barrow Creek area.<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2005/dec/13/australia.world</ref>\n\n[[Christopher Buckley (novelist)|Christopher Buckley]] made reference to these shootings in a 1995 commencement speech at his alma mater of [[Portsmouth Abbey School]], where he commented on Chapman's possession of the book and later remarked \"''Catcher in the Rye'' is a fine piece of literature and well worth your time, if you have not so read it already. So long as does not inspire you to shoot any of the remaining Beatles.\" <ref>https://www.upi.com/topic/Christopher_Buckley/</ref>\n\n==Films==\nAlthough Salinger had refused a [[film adaptation]], many Hollywood films have based characters on Holden Caulfield.<ref name=\"SFGate\" /><ref name=\"PNT\">{{cite news | author=Robert Wilonsky | title=Burr, Not Chilly | url=http://www.phoenixnewtimes.com/2002-09-19/film/burr-not-chilly/ | work=[[Phoenix New Times]] | date=2002-09-19 | accessdate=2007-12-19 | quote=Salinger would never allow such a thing, and it's a moot point, to boot. Catcher has been made and remade for decades under various ''noms de crap''...}}</ref> Holden has been identified as \"one of the most reproduced characters on film.\" Furthermore, many such films reference each other.<ref name=\"Onstad\">{{cite news | author=Katrina Onstad | title=Beholden to Holden | url=http://www.cbc.ca/arts/film/bartlett.html | work=[[CBC News]] | date=2008-02-22}}</ref>\n\nAnthony Caputi, a specialist in dramatic literature at [[Cornell University]], claims that the novel inspires both \"variations\" and \"imitations\", comparing it with several [[coming-of-age]] films.<ref name=\"SFGate\">{{cite news | author=Nancy Mills | title=Holden Caulfield's many pretenders | url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/chronicle/archive/2002/08/25/PK45441.DTL&type=movies | work=[[San Francisco Chronicle]] | date=2002-08-25 | accessdate = 2007-05-21 | quote='Most young male characters in the movies are based on the character of Holden Caulfield,' says Raymond Haberski... 'It's been a very steady influence in the last 30 years.'}}</ref>\n* In ''[[The Collector]]'' (1965), which is based on the [[John Fowles]] novel, Clegg cannot understand why Miranda likes ''The Catcher in the Rye''.<ref>{{cite web | author=Kirsten Markson | url=http://www.popmatters.com/film/reviews/c/collector.shtml | title=The Collector | work=[[PopMatters]] | date=2002-11-03 | accessdate=2007-12-19}}</ref>\n* In the 1990 play and 1993 film ''[[Six Degrees of Separation (film)|Six Degrees of Separation]]'', the impostor Paul gives an analysis on the novel in a monologue.<ref>{{cite news | author=Rita Kempley | title=Six Degrees of Separation | work=[[The Washington Post]] | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/style/longterm/movies/videos/sixdegreesofseparationrkempley_a0a3dd.htm | date=1993-12-22 | accessdate=2007-12-19 | quote=Guare ... expounds upon ... the violent subtext of ''The Catcher in the Rye''...}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | author=William A. Henry III | title=Six Degrees of Separation | url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,970446,00.html | work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] | date=1990-06-25 | accessdate=2007-12-19 | quote=When the intruder starts to analyze ''The Catcher in the Rye'' in scholarly jargon, the hosts are spellbound by his vocabulary and miss the fact that his rap becomes comic nonsense.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | author=Lauren Phillips | title=Color without structure | url=http://media.www.tuftsdaily.com/media/storage/paper856/news/2002/04/01/UndefinedSection/Color.Without.Structure-1484266.shtml | archive-url=https://archive.today/20090110154302/http://media.www.tuftsdaily.com/media/storage/paper856/news/2002/04/01/UndefinedSection/Color.Without.Structure-1484266.shtml | url-status=dead | archive-date=2009-01-10 | work=[[The Tufts Daily]] | date=2002-04-01 | accessdate=2007-12-19 | quote=...Paul's frequent references to Holden Caufield's struggles in Catcher in the Rye. }}</ref> According to him, the novel, a \"manifesto of hate\" against phonies, would have been the excuse<ref>{{cite news | author=Frank Rich | title=Stage View; A Guidebook to the Soul Of a City in Confusion | url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9C0CE3D9173DF932A35754C0A966958260&sec=&spon=&pagewanted=all | work=[[The New York Times]] | date=1990-07-01 | accessdate = 2007-12-19 | quote=...in Paul's view, that J. D. Salinger's 'touching, beautiful, sensitive story' has been turned into 'a manifesto of hate' by assassins like Mark David Chapman and John Hinckley who use Holden Caulfield's social estrangement as an excuse to commit murder.}}</ref> or defense<ref>Whitfield, 573.</ref> for Chapman and Hinckley's shootings.\n* In ''[[Conspiracy Theory (film)|Conspiracy Theory]]'' (1997), Mel Gibson's character is programmed to buy the novel whenever he sees it, though he never actually reads it.<ref name=\"Salon\"/>\n* ''Chasing Holden'' (2001) is named after Holden Caulfield.<ref>{{cite news | author=Michael Speier | title='Holden' catches cast | url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117795994.html?categoryid=13&cs=1 | work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] | date=2001-03-28 | accessdate=2007-05-21 | quote=Title is a reference to ''The Catcher in the Rye'' protag Holden Caulfield, around whom Kanan's script is based.}}</ref> The protagonist Neil relates his life to Holden's, skips class to go to [[New York City]], goes on a road trip to [[New Hampshire]] to find Salinger, and contemplates killing Salinger.<ref>{{cite web | author=[[Christopher Null]] | title=Chasing Holden Movie Review | work=[[Filmcritic.com]] | url=http://www.filmcritic.com/misc/emporium.nsf/84dbbfa4d710144986256c290016f76e/c313d5eea351d56a88256bcc00699931?OpenDocument | year=2002 | accessdate=2007-05-21 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071104235038/http://www.filmcritic.com/misc/emporium.nsf/84dbbfa4d710144986256c290016f76e/c313d5eea351d56a88256bcc00699931?OpenDocument | archivedate=2007-11-04 }}</ref>\n* Screenwriter [[Mike White (scriptwriter)|Mike White]] regards the novel as \"part of a literary trend that goes back to Goethe's ''[[The Sorrows of Young Werther|The Sorrows of Werther]]'' (1774) ... I don't think Salinger discovered it. He just did the quintessential American version.\"<ref name=\"SFGate\" /> He thought the influence of the novel may rise in Hollywood,<ref name=\"SFGate\" /> and two of his 2002 films reflect this. In ''[[Orange County (film)|Orange County]]'', protagonist Shaun searches for the professor who wrote the book that changed his life.<ref name=\"SFGate\" />\n* In ''[[The Good Girl]]'', protagonist Thomas Worther calls himself Holden and is seen reading the novel.<ref name=\"SFGate\" /><ref name=\"PNT\" />\n* ''[[Igby Goes Down]]'' (2002), originally intended to be a novel, has been interpreted as being inspired by ''The Catcher in the Rye'',<ref name=\"PNT\" /><ref name=\"Onstad\" /><ref>{{cite news | author=J.J. Duncan | title=Film Review: Stellar performers, quirky characters make Salinger rip-off worth seeing | work=Kansas State Collegian | url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-69313860.html | date=2002-11-04 | accessdate=2007-12-19 | quote=Screenwriting 101: Ripping off Salinger is a quick way of writing a decent movie about teen-age disillusionment.}}{{dead link|date=February 2019|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | author=Terry Lawson | title=Reviews and ratings of feature films | url=http://www.accessmylibrary.com/coms2/summary_0286-8936760_ITM | work=[[Detroit Free Press]] | date=2002-11-14 | accessdate=2007-12-19 | quote=''Catcher in the Rye'' gone awry, this angst-filled dark comedy finds a prep-school dropout set adrift in New York City.}}</ref> but director and screenwriter [[Burr Steers]] said it is not a direct influence and the story is more of an autobiography.<ref name=\"SFGate\" /> On the influence of the book, Steers \"liken[s] it to being a musician and being influenced by the music ingrained in you, like [[the Beatles]].\"<ref name=\"SFGate\" />\n* ''The Catcher in the Rye'' deeply influenced the 2017 biographical drama film ''[[Rebel in the Rye]]'', which is about Salinger. It is a visual about his life, before and after World War II, and gives more about the author's life than the readers of ''The Catcher in the Rye'' learned from the novel.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2017/09/rebel-in-the-rye-review/538908/ |title='Rebel in the Rye' Is Phony Through and Through |last=Sims |first=David |work=The Atlantic|access-date=May 22, 2018 |language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==Television==\n* The main plot for the Japanese anime television series ''[[Ghost in the Shell: Stand Alone Complex]]'' (2002) hinges on elements from ''The Catcher in the Rye'' from which a character uses a digital logo representing Holden Caulfield, and the quote \"I thought what I'd do was, I'd pretend I was one of those deaf-mutes.\"<ref>{{cite news | author=Charles Solomon | title=\u2018Ghost in the Shell\u2019: Three TV variations on a cyberpunk theme | work=Los Angeles Times | url=http://herocomplex.latimes.com/movies/ghost-in-the-shell-three-tv-variations-on-a-cyberpunk-theme | date=2011-06-22}}</ref> These themes and some additional quotes are also expressed in ''Stand Alone Complex 2nd GIG'' (2004), although the characters and plot have changed.\n* ''[[South Park]]'' episode \"[[The Tale of Scrotie McBoogerballs]]\" (2010) makes particular reference to ''The Catcher in the Rye'' and shows that its once-controversial use of vocabulary has no impact among young readers nowadays, and pokes fun at literary critics reading deeper meaning into books. It also references its connection towards the series of high-profile assassination attempts in the 1980s, with character [[Butters Stotch]] expressing a desire to kill John Lennon after reading the book until his father tells him that Lennon was already killed.<ref>{{cite web | author=Ramsey Isler | title= South Park: \"The Tale of Scrotie McBoogerballs\" Review | work=IGN | url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2010/03/25/south-park-the-tale-of-scrotie-mcboogerballs-review | date=2010-03-25}}</ref>\n\n==Books==\n''The Catcher in the Rye'' has had significant cultural influence, and works inspired by the novel have been said to form their own genre. Sarah Graham assessed works influenced by ''The Catcher in the Rye'' to include the novels ''[[Less Than Zero (novel)|Less Than Zero]]'' by [[Bret Easton Ellis]], ''[[The Perks of Being a Wallflower]]'' by [[Stephen Chbosky]], ''[[A Complicated Kindness]]'' by [[Miriam Toews]], ''[[The Bell Jar]]'' by [[Sylvia Plath]], ''[[Ordinary People (novel)|Ordinary People]]'' by [[Judith Guest]], and the film ''[[Igby Goes Down]]'' by [[Burr Steers]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Rohrer |first=Finlo |date=June 5, 2009 |title=Why does Salinger's Catcher in the Rye still resonate? |work=BBC News Magazine |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/magazine/8084931.stm |accessdate=February 12, 2012}}</ref>\n* [[John Fowles]]'s 1963 novel ''[[The Collector]]'' uses ''The Catcher in the Rye'' as \"one of the most brilliant examples of adolescence\" in popular culture, possibly under a moral light.<ref>Whitfield, 570.</ref> In it, Miranda encourages her kidnapper Clegg to read ''Catcher'', thinking he might relate to Holden's alienation.<ref name=\"Salon\" /> However, Clegg finds Holden's actions unrealistic given Holden's wealth and status, and \"[doesn't] see much point in it.\" In the film adaptation of ''The Collector'', this conversation and Clegg's attitude toward the novel and popular culture is subdued.<ref>Whitfield, 571.</ref> The novel has itself been linked to several serial killers.<ref name=\"Salon\" />\n* [[Alberto Fuguet]]'s first novel ''[[Mala onda]]'' (''Bad Vibes'', 1991), which is set in [[Santiago, Chile]] three months before the John Lennon assassination, references ''The Catcher in the Rye'' extensively.<ref>Santini, Beno\u00eet (2013). ''Chile en el siglo XXI: \u00bfNuevos recorridos art\u00edsticos, nuevos caminos hist\u00f3ricos?''. Mago Editores.</ref> Like Holden, Mat\u00edas Vicu\u00f1a (the 17-year-old narrator and protagonist of the novel) is a cynical, alienated, upper-class teenager who feels fed-up with the blandness of his friends and family. After reading Salinger's book, Mat\u00edas feels a special connection with Holden. He attempts to replicate Holden's self-inflicted isolation by fleeing home and locking himself up in a hotel room, and he even purchases a red hunting hat to complete the persona.<ref>[[Alberto Fuguet|Fuguet, Alberto]] (1997). ''[[Mala onda|Bad Vibes]]''. [[St. Martin's Press]].</ref>\n* [[Lawrence Block]] wrote a novel called ''Burglar in the Rye'' (1999) in his series on burglar [[Bernie Rhodenbarr]]. The plot focuses on an auction of a reclusive writer's letters,<ref>{{cite news |author1=Harry Levins |author2=Susan C. Hegger |author3=Judith Evans | title=Thrillers | url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=SL&p_theme=sl&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EB0519F0B8A5A62&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D | work=[[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]] | date=1999-07-04 | accessdate=2007-05-21 | format=fee required | quote = ''Burglar in the Rye''; referring to whiskey, in a wry twist that centers on the planned auction of letters from a reclusive writer who authored a seminal...}}</ref> and Bernie works to track down the character based on J. D. Salinger.\n* In [[Galt Niederhoffer]]'s novel ''A Taxonomy of Barnacles'' (2005), Bridget and Billy think about Holden's question as to the whereabouts of ducks during winter.<ref>{{cite news | author=Ashley Simpson Shires | title='Barnacles' gets tangled | url=http://www.rockymountainnews.com/drmn/books/article/0,2792,DRMN_63_4349766,00.html | work=[[Rocky Mountain News]] | date=2005-12-30 | accessdate=2007-05-21 | quote=Niederhoffer nods to Salinger in a reference to ''The Catcher in the Rye'': Bridget and Billy pause on 72nd Street, near the Boat Pond, 'pondering Holden's question: where on earth did the ducks go during the winter months?' | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070206133118/http://www.rockymountainnews.com/drmn/books/article/0,2792,DRMN_63_4349766,00.html | archivedate=2007-02-06}}</ref>\n* [[John David California]] wrote ''60 Years Later: Coming Through the Rye'' (2009), an unauthorized sequel in which seventy-six-year-old Holden escapes a retirement home for a journey in New York.<ref>{{cite news | author=Alison Flood | title=Catcher in the Rye sequel published \u2013 but not by Salinger | url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2009/may/14/catcher-in-the-rye-sequel | work=[[The Guardian]] | date=2009-05-14}}</ref>\n* [[Bob Uecker]], a former [[Major League Baseball]] catcher named his book \"Catcher in the Wry\", a pun on the title of the Catcher in the Rye. His book recounts anecdotes of his years behind the plate and on the road, recalling the antics of his famous teammates, including Hank Aaron, Bob Gibson, Richie Allen, and Warren Spahn.\n* Fantasy writer [[Harry Turtledove]] has written a pastiche-parody \"Catcher in the Rhine\", based on his daughter's mishearing of Salinger's title. In this short story, an unnamed narrator, who is clearly meant to be Holden Caulfield but is unnamed to avoid copyright problems, goes on vacation to Germany and meets characters from the ''[[Nibelungenlied]]''. This was first published in ''[[The Chick is in the Mail]]'', edited by [[Esther Friesner]], [[Baen]] 2000 and reprinted in the omnibus ''Chicks Ahoy!'' (2010). It was reprinted in ''Atlantis and Other Places'' also in 2010.\n\n==Comic strips and Magazines==\n* The ''[[Frazz]]'' character Caulfield is named after Holden.<ref>{{cite news | author=Pat Hathcock | title=New comic strip debuts in today's Advocate | url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=VA&p_theme=va&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0FAD78EC6E0A4009&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D | work=Victoria Advocate| date=2003-05-05 | accessdate=2008-01-04}}</ref>\nThe July 1985 issue of ''[[National Lampoon (magazine)|National Lampoon]]'' included a parody of the novel, ostensibly written by Holden Caulfield's son, entitled ''The Son of the Catcher, who Lives in Rye''.\n\n==Music==\n\n* [[Night Ranger]]' 1982 song \"Night Ranger\" from their album ''[[Dawn Patrol (album)|Dawn Patrol]]'' mentions Catcher in the Rye.\nIn the heat of the night\nLooking for adventure\nOn the face of the light\nA Colorado school boy\nPut his days on the line\nNights out of paperback\n\"Catcher In The Rye\"\n\n* [[The Ataris]]' song \"If You Really Want to Hear About It\" from their album ''[[End is Forever]]'' takes its title from the novel's opening sentence. The final lines paraphrase those of the book with \"Don't ever tell anyone anything or else you'll wind up missing everybody.\" Several other specific references are made within the lyrics.<ref>{{cite news|author=Jung La |title=Ataris: End is Forever |url=http://daily.stanford.edu/article/2001/4/12/atarisEndIsForever |work=[[The Stanford Daily]] |date=2001-04-12 |accessdate=2007-06-08 |quote=The pop culture saturation of the Ataris\u2019 lyrics could get annoying if you\u2019re not into that sort of thing, but, to me, it\u2019s what makes this album stand out. \u201cIf You Really Want To Hear About It\u201d references J. D. Salinger\u2019s \u201cCatcher in the Rye\u201d... }}{{dead link|date=May 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n* [[Billy Joel]]'s \"[[We Didn't Start the Fire]]\" mentions the novel as a historic item of note during his lifetime.<ref>{{cite news | author=Chris Heim | title=Billy Joel and the `We Didn't Start the Fire' quiz | url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/chicagotribune/access/28797913.html?dids=28797913:28797913&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&date=Feb+09%2C+1990&author=Chris+Heim&pub=Chicago+Tribune+(pre-1997+Fulltext)&desc=Billy+Joel+and+the+%60We+Didn%27t+Start+the+Fire%27+quiz | work=[[Chicago Tribune]] | date=1990-02-09 | format=fee required}}</ref>\n* [[Green Day]]'s \"Who Wrote Holden Caulfield?\" from their album ''[[Kerplunk (album)|Kerplunk]]'' (1991) is named after and is about the novel's main character, [[Holden Caulfield]]. Frontman [[Billie Joe Armstrong]] recalled being forced to read the novel in high school and despising it. He later reread it as an adult, because it was seen as \"punk rock\".<ref>https://genius.com/Green-day-who-wrote-holden-caulfield-lyrics</ref>\n* [[Belle and Sebastian]]'s song \"Le Pastie De La Bourgeoisie\" from their 1997 EP ''[[3.. 6.. 9 Seconds of Light]]'' features the lyric \"Wouldn't you like to get away? Give yourself up to the allure of Catcher in the Rye, the future's swathed in stars and stripes\".\n* [[Guns and Roses]] album ''[[Chinese Democracy]]'' includes a song called [[Catcher in the Rye]] in which the narrator debates a violent fantasy.\n* Ska-Punk band [[Five Iron Frenzy]]'s song \"Superpowers\" includes the lyrics, \"I sometimes feel I'm Holden Caulfield, sometimes Jack Kerouac. I wanted to be famous, now I want to take it back.\".\n* Francesco Guccini's 1970 song \"La collina\" (The Hill) is openly inspired by this novel.\n\n==Gaming==\nThe video game ''Bully'' had the protagonist forced to attend a Connecticut boarding school. Just after being dropped off, he remarks about his mother's remarriage, calling his new stepfather a \"phony\". [[Rockstar Games]], the producer of ''Bully'', said part of the concept was inspired by ''Catcher in the Rye''.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite journal | title = Cherished and Cursed: Toward a Social History of The Catcher in the Rye | last = Whitfield | first = Stephen | journal = The New England Quarterly | volume = 70 | issue = 4 | date = December 1997 | pages = 567\u2013600 | doi = 10.2307/366646 | jstor = 366646 <!-- Article released for free download by publisher at http://www.northeastern.edu/neq/Announcements.html as per \"Free Article: A Social History of The Catcher in the Rye\", January 27, 2010 --> | url = http://www.northeastern.edu/neq/pdfs/Whitfield%2C_Stephen_J.pdf | format = PDF | accessdate = 2012-11-02  | ref = harv | url-status=dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120912144104/http://www.northeastern.edu/neq/pdfs/Whitfield%2C_Stephen_J.pdf | archivedate = September 12, 2012 | df =  | postscript = <br />. Reprinted in}} {{Cite book |title= J. D. Salinger |year=2001 |publisher= [[Chelsea House]] |location=Philadelphia |series= Bloom's BioCritiques |isbn=0-7910-6175-2 |editor1-last= Bloom |editor1-first= Harold |editor1-link= Harold Bloom | pages = 77\u2013105}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cultural references to the novel The Catcher In The Rye}}\n[[Category:Novels in popular culture|Catcher in the Rye, The]]\n", "text_old": "{{More citations needed|date=May 2012}}\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:''The Catcher in the Rye'' in popular culture}}\nThe 1951 novel '''''[[The Catcher in the Rye]]''''' by [[J. D. Salinger]] has had a lasting influence<ref name=\"WP\">{{cite news\n| url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A43680-2004Oct18.html\n| title = J.D. Salinger's Holden Caulfield, Aging Gracelessly\n| author = Jonathan Yardley\n| work = [[The Washington Post]]\n| date = 2004-10-19\n| accessdate = 2007-05-21\n| quote = \"The Catcher in the Rye\" is a maladroit, mawkish novel, but there can be no question about its popularity or influence.\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n| url = http://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=FB0C17FD345912738DDDAC0894D9405B848AF1D3\n| title = Brooklyn College\n| author = Barry Roth\n| work = [[The New York Times]]\n| date = 1964-01-05\n| accessdate = 2007-05-21\n| quote = ...the \"do you think you'll ever feel about me the way you used to feel about 'Catcher in the Rye'?\" influence of the theater and movies often stimulates collegians to read these and other writers.\n}}</ref> as it remains both a [[bestseller]]<ref name=\"Guinn\" /> and a [[List of most commonly challenged books in the U.S.|frequently challenged book]].<ref name=\"Guinn\">{{cite news\n| url = http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=ET&p_theme=et&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EDCAD301800C85B&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D\n| title = 'Catcher in the Rye' still influences 50 years later\n| author = Jeff Guinn\n| work = [[Erie Times-News]]\n| date = 2001-08-10\n| accessdate = 2007-12-18\n| format = fee required\n}} [http://www.accessmylibrary.com/coms2/summary_0286-6739335_ITM Alternate URL].</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.ala.org/ala/oif/bannedbooksweek/bbwlinks/100mostfrequently.htm\n |title=100 Most Frequently Challenged Books of 1990\u20132000\n |publisher=[[American Library Association]]\n |accessdate=2007-01-21\n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070118015806/http://www.ala.org/ala/oif/bannedbooksweek/bbwlinks/100mostfrequently.htm\n |archivedate=2007-01-18\n |url-status=dead\n}}</ref> Numerous works in [[popular culture]] have referenced the novel.<ref name=\"SB\">{{cite news\n| url = http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=SB&p_theme=sb&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EC831DF2A54202C&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D\n| title = 'Rye' misfit's rugged spirit inspires works\n| work = [[The Sacramento Bee]]\n| date = 2001-06-07\n| accessdate = 2007-05-21\n| format = fee required\n| quote = \"The Catcher in the Rye\" has influenced the work of many writers, filmmakers and musicians. Here's a look at some of the more notable entries...\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n| url = http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=WO&p_theme=wo&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EB9EAB0A95F7BFF&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D\n| title = Sixties to Howl Once Again in College Literature Course\n| work = [[Telegram & Gazette]]\n| date = 2001-04-08\n| accessdate = 2007-05-21\n| format = fee required\n| quote = Mr. Patterson explained his inclusion of a 1952 novel in his \"Literature of the 1960s\" course this way: \"I kept seeing references to Holden Caulfield...\n}}</ref>\nFactors contributing to the novel's mystique and impact include its portrayal of protagonist [[Holden Caulfield]];<ref name=\"WP\" /> its tone of sincerity;<ref name=\"WP\" /> its themes of familial neglect,<ref name=\"SFGate\" /> tension between teens and society,<ref name=\"Guinn\" /><ref name=\"SFGate\" /> and rebellion;<ref name=\"SFGate\" /> its previous banned status;<ref>{{cite news\n| url = http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=HT&p_theme=ht&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EAFEA3BF023F923&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D\n| title = Banned Books Offer Classic Opportunities\n| work = [[Sarasota Herald-Tribune]]\n| date = 1996-10-23\n| accessdate = 2007-05-21\n| format = fee required\n| quote = [...] one of the controversial books that has been censored in the past is J.D. Salinger's ``The Catcher in the Rye.' [...] all through his life he'd hear references to Holden Caulfield and his crazy red hunting hat, and if he wanted to understand those references, [...]\n}}</ref> and Salinger's reclusiveness.<ref name=\"WP\" />\n\n''The Catcher in the Rye'' has inspired \"rewrites\" which have been said to form their own genre.<ref name=\"Menand\">{{cite news\n| title = Holden at fifty\n| author = [[Louis Menand]]\n| work = [[The New Yorker]]\n| date = 2001-09-27\n}}</ref>\nOn the other hand, there are examples of similarities between the novel and other works that were not intended by their authors,<ref name=\"SFGate\" /><ref>{{cite news\n |url         = http://www.dailyprincetonian.com/archives/2005/11/09/news/13716.shtml\n |title       = Novelist Sittenfeld chronicles 'Prep' life\n |author      = Joy Karugu\n |work        = [[The Daily Princetonian]]\n |date        = 2005-11-09\n |accessdate  = 2007-12-19\n |quote       = That's an easy comparison people often make \u2014 because of its setting and general topic.\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20081002030516/http://www.dailyprincetonian.com/archives/2005/11/09/news/13716.shtml\n |archivedate = 2008-10-02\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n| url = https://www.nytimes.com/2007/09/23/books/review/Peck-t.html?pagewanted=print\n| title = \u2018The Outsiders\u2019: 40 Years Later\n| author = Dale Peck\n| work = [[New York Times]]\n| date = 2007-09-23\n| accessdate = 2007-12-19\n| quote = ...it\u2019s likely that Hinton\u2019s echo of the testimonial frame Salinger used in \u201cThe Catcher in the Rye\u201d (\u201cIf you really want to hear about it\u201d) wasn\u2019t consciously intended...\n}}</ref> which suggests that the novel is \"present, at least spiritually, in ... any story line that involves quirky young people struggling to find their places in a society prone to reward conformity and condemn individuality.\"<ref name=\"Guinn\" />\n\nWhile the novel is linked to several murders and murder attempts, it has been claimed that the novel's overall effect on society is \"far more positive than negative.\"<ref name=\"Guinn\" />\n\nThe novel also helped popularize the slang verb \"screw up\".<ref>{{cite news\n| url = https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9C0CE2DF1138F93BA35757C0A966958260&sec=&spon=&pagewanted=2\n| title = Screwing Up\n| author = William Safire\n| work = [[The New York Times]]\n| date = 1990-04-08\n| accessdate = 2007-12-20\n| pages = 2\n| quote = Screw up, in this sense, is first found in a December 1942 issue of Yank, and was further popularized in the 1951 ''Catcher in the Rye,'' the famed novel by J. D. Salinger: ''Boy, it really screws up my sex life something awful.''\n}}</ref>\n\nIn recent years{{when|date=March 2019}} there has been a discussion of depression as exhibited in Holden Caulfield.<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Depression in J.D. Salinger's The Catcher in the Rye\n| editor = Dedria Bryfonski\n| work = [[Greenhaven Press]]\n| date = 2009\n}}</ref>\n\n==Shootings==\nThe best-known event associated with ''The Catcher in the Rye'' is arguably [[Mark David Chapman]]'s [[Murder of John Lennon|shooting of John Lennon]].<ref>{{cite news\n| url = https://www.usatoday.com/news/index/colo/colo22.htm\n| title = Kids, online and off, feast on violence\n|author1=Leslie Miller |author2=Susan Wlosczyczna |author3=Joh Chetwynd |author4=Gary Levin |author5=Claudia Puig |author6=Mike Snider |author7=Kevin V. Johnson | work = [[USA Today]]\n| date = 1999-04-22\n| accessdate = 2007-05-21\n| quote = [[Lindsay Doran]], president of [[United Artists]], says, \"[...] You can't not like ''Catcher in the Rye'' because someone read it and killed John Lennon.\"\n}}</ref>\nChapman identified with the novel's narrator to the extent that he wanted to change his name to Holden Caulfield. On the night he shot Lennon, Chapman was found with a copy of the book in which he had written \"<u>This</u> is my statement\" and signed Holden's name.<ref name=\"Salon\">{{cite web\n |url         = http://dir.salon.com/story/books/feature/2003/12/15/books_kill/index1.html\n |title       = When books kill\n |author      = Aidan Doyle\n |publisher   = [[Salon.com]]\n |date        = 2003-12-15\n |accessdate  = 2007-05-21\n |pages       = 2\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20071105025510/http://dir.salon.com/story/books/feature/2003/12/15/books_kill/index1.html\n |archivedate = 2007-11-05\n}}</ref> Later, he read a passage from the novel to address the court during his sentencing.<ref name=\"Whitfield, 571\u2013572\">Whitfield, 571\u2013572.</ref> [[Daniel Stashower]] speculated that Chapman had wanted Lennon's innocence to be preserved by death, inspired by Holden's wish to preserve children's innocence despite Holden's later realization that children should be left alone.<ref name=\"Whitfield, 571\u2013572\"/>\n\nAfter [[John Hinckley, Jr.]]'s [[Reagan assassination attempt|assassination attempt]] on [[Ronald Reagan]] in 1981, police found ''The Catcher in the Rye'' among half a dozen other books in his hotel room.<ref>Whitfield, 572.</ref>\n\n[[Robert John Bardo]], who murdered [[Rebecca Schaeffer]], was carrying the book when he visited Schaeffer's apartment in Hollywood on July 18, 1989 and murdered her.<ref>\n{{cite web\n| url = http://www.amarillo.com/stories/091000/boo_tellingondad.shtml\n| title = Telling on Dad\n| author = Linton Weeks\n| publisher = [[Amarillo Globe-News]]\n| date = 2000-09-10\n| accessdate = 2009-01-13\n| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110604005125/http://amarillo.com/stories/091000/boo_tellingondad.shtml\n| archive-date = 2011-06-04\n| url-status = dead\n}}\n</ref>\n\n[[Peter Falconio]] was reported to be reading the novel prior to  his disappearance from the Barrow Creek area.<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2005/dec/13/australia.world</ref>\n\n[[Christopher Buckley]] made reference to these shootings in a 1995 commencement speech at his alma mater of [[Portsmouth Abbey School]], where he commented on Chapman's possession of the book and later remarked \"''Catcher in the Rye'' is a fine piece of literature and well worth your time, if you have not so read it already. So long as does not inspire you to shoot any of the remaining Beatles.\" <ref>https://www.upi.com/topic/Christopher_Buckley/</ref>\n\n==Films==\nAlthough Salinger had refused a [[film adaptation]], many Hollywood films have based characters on Holden Caulfield.<ref name=\"SFGate\" /><ref name=\"PNT\">{{cite news | author=Robert Wilonsky | title=Burr, Not Chilly | url=http://www.phoenixnewtimes.com/2002-09-19/film/burr-not-chilly/ | work=[[Phoenix New Times]] | date=2002-09-19 | accessdate=2007-12-19 | quote=Salinger would never allow such a thing, and it's a moot point, to boot. Catcher has been made and remade for decades under various ''noms de crap''...}}</ref> Holden has been identified as \"one of the most reproduced characters on film.\" Furthermore, many such films reference each other.<ref name=\"Onstad\">{{cite news | author=Katrina Onstad | title=Beholden to Holden | url=http://www.cbc.ca/arts/film/bartlett.html | work=[[CBC News]] | date=2008-02-22}}</ref>\n\nAnthony Caputi, a specialist in dramatic literature at [[Cornell University]], claims that the novel inspires both \"variations\" and \"imitations\", comparing it with several [[coming-of-age]] films.<ref name=\"SFGate\">{{cite news | author=Nancy Mills | title=Holden Caulfield's many pretenders | url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/chronicle/archive/2002/08/25/PK45441.DTL&type=movies | work=[[San Francisco Chronicle]] | date=2002-08-25 | accessdate = 2007-05-21 | quote='Most young male characters in the movies are based on the character of Holden Caulfield,' says Raymond Haberski... 'It's been a very steady influence in the last 30 years.'}}</ref>\n* In ''[[The Collector]]'' (1965), which is based on the [[John Fowles]] novel, Clegg cannot understand why Miranda likes ''The Catcher in the Rye''.<ref>{{cite web | author=Kirsten Markson | url=http://www.popmatters.com/film/reviews/c/collector.shtml | title=The Collector | work=[[PopMatters]] | date=2002-11-03 | accessdate=2007-12-19}}</ref>\n* In the 1990 play and 1993 film ''[[Six Degrees of Separation (film)|Six Degrees of Separation]]'', the impostor Paul gives an analysis on the novel in a monologue.<ref>{{cite news | author=Rita Kempley | title=Six Degrees of Separation | work=[[The Washington Post]] | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/style/longterm/movies/videos/sixdegreesofseparationrkempley_a0a3dd.htm | date=1993-12-22 | accessdate=2007-12-19 | quote=Guare ... expounds upon ... the violent subtext of ''The Catcher in the Rye''...}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | author=William A. Henry III | title=Six Degrees of Separation | url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,970446,00.html | work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] | date=1990-06-25 | accessdate=2007-12-19 | quote=When the intruder starts to analyze ''The Catcher in the Rye'' in scholarly jargon, the hosts are spellbound by his vocabulary and miss the fact that his rap becomes comic nonsense.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | author=Lauren Phillips | title=Color without structure | url=http://media.www.tuftsdaily.com/media/storage/paper856/news/2002/04/01/UndefinedSection/Color.Without.Structure-1484266.shtml | archive-url=https://archive.today/20090110154302/http://media.www.tuftsdaily.com/media/storage/paper856/news/2002/04/01/UndefinedSection/Color.Without.Structure-1484266.shtml | url-status=dead | archive-date=2009-01-10 | work=[[The Tufts Daily]] | date=2002-04-01 | accessdate=2007-12-19 | quote=...Paul's frequent references to Holden Caufield's struggles in Catcher in the Rye. }}</ref> According to him, the novel, a \"manifesto of hate\" against phonies, would have been the excuse<ref>{{cite news | author=Frank Rich | title=Stage View; A Guidebook to the Soul Of a City in Confusion | url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9C0CE3D9173DF932A35754C0A966958260&sec=&spon=&pagewanted=all | work=[[The New York Times]] | date=1990-07-01 | accessdate = 2007-12-19 | quote=...in Paul's view, that J. D. Salinger's 'touching, beautiful, sensitive story' has been turned into 'a manifesto of hate' by assassins like Mark David Chapman and John Hinckley who use Holden Caulfield's social estrangement as an excuse to commit murder.}}</ref> or defense<ref>Whitfield, 573.</ref> for Chapman and Hinckley's shootings.\n* In ''[[Conspiracy Theory (film)|Conspiracy Theory]]'' (1997), Mel Gibson's character is programmed to buy the novel whenever he sees it, though he never actually reads it.<ref name=\"Salon\"/>\n* ''Chasing Holden'' (2001) is named after Holden Caulfield.<ref>{{cite news | author=Michael Speier | title='Holden' catches cast | url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117795994.html?categoryid=13&cs=1 | work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] | date=2001-03-28 | accessdate=2007-05-21 | quote=Title is a reference to ''The Catcher in the Rye'' protag Holden Caulfield, around whom Kanan's script is based.}}</ref> The protagonist Neil relates his life to Holden's, skips class to go to [[New York City]], goes on a road trip to [[New Hampshire]] to find Salinger, and contemplates killing Salinger.<ref>{{cite web | author=[[Christopher Null]] | title=Chasing Holden Movie Review | work=[[Filmcritic.com]] | url=http://www.filmcritic.com/misc/emporium.nsf/84dbbfa4d710144986256c290016f76e/c313d5eea351d56a88256bcc00699931?OpenDocument | year=2002 | accessdate=2007-05-21 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071104235038/http://www.filmcritic.com/misc/emporium.nsf/84dbbfa4d710144986256c290016f76e/c313d5eea351d56a88256bcc00699931?OpenDocument | archivedate=2007-11-04 }}</ref>\n* Screenwriter [[Mike White (scriptwriter)|Mike White]] regards the novel as \"part of a literary trend that goes back to Goethe's ''[[The Sorrows of Young Werther|The Sorrows of Werther]]'' (1774) ... I don't think Salinger discovered it. He just did the quintessential American version.\"<ref name=\"SFGate\" /> He thought the influence of the novel may rise in Hollywood,<ref name=\"SFGate\" /> and two of his 2002 films reflect this. In ''[[Orange County (film)|Orange County]]'', protagonist Shaun searches for the professor who wrote the book that changed his life.<ref name=\"SFGate\" />\n* In ''[[The Good Girl]]'', protagonist Thomas Worther calls himself Holden and is seen reading the novel.<ref name=\"SFGate\" /><ref name=\"PNT\" />\n* ''[[Igby Goes Down]]'' (2002), originally intended to be a novel, has been interpreted as being inspired by ''The Catcher in the Rye'',<ref name=\"PNT\" /><ref name=\"Onstad\" /><ref>{{cite news | author=J.J. Duncan | title=Film Review: Stellar performers, quirky characters make Salinger rip-off worth seeing | work=Kansas State Collegian | url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-69313860.html | date=2002-11-04 | accessdate=2007-12-19 | quote=Screenwriting 101: Ripping off Salinger is a quick way of writing a decent movie about teen-age disillusionment.}}{{dead link|date=February 2019|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | author=Terry Lawson | title=Reviews and ratings of feature films | url=http://www.accessmylibrary.com/coms2/summary_0286-8936760_ITM | work=[[Detroit Free Press]] | date=2002-11-14 | accessdate=2007-12-19 | quote=''Catcher in the Rye'' gone awry, this angst-filled dark comedy finds a prep-school dropout set adrift in New York City.}}</ref> but director and screenwriter [[Burr Steers]] said it is not a direct influence and the story is more of an autobiography.<ref name=\"SFGate\" /> On the influence of the book, Steers \"liken[s] it to being a musician and being influenced by the music ingrained in you, like [[the Beatles]].\"<ref name=\"SFGate\" />\n* ''The Catcher in the Rye'' deeply influenced the 2017 biographical drama film ''[[Rebel in the Rye]]'', which is about Salinger. It is a visual about his life, before and after World War II, and gives more about the author's life than the readers of ''The Catcher in the Rye'' learned from the novel.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2017/09/rebel-in-the-rye-review/538908/ |title='Rebel in the Rye' Is Phony Through and Through |last=Sims |first=David |work=The Atlantic|access-date=May 22, 2018 |language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==Television==\n* The main plot for the Japanese anime television series ''[[Ghost in the Shell: Stand Alone Complex]]'' (2002) hinges on elements from ''The Catcher in the Rye'' from which a character uses a digital logo representing Holden Caulfield, and the quote \"I thought what I'd do was, I'd pretend I was one of those deaf-mutes.\"<ref>{{cite news | author=Charles Solomon | title=\u2018Ghost in the Shell\u2019: Three TV variations on a cyberpunk theme | work=Los Angeles Times | url=http://herocomplex.latimes.com/movies/ghost-in-the-shell-three-tv-variations-on-a-cyberpunk-theme | date=2011-06-22}}</ref> These themes and some additional quotes are also expressed in ''Stand Alone Complex 2nd GIG'' (2004), although the characters and plot have changed.\n* ''[[South Park]]'' episode \"[[The Tale of Scrotie McBoogerballs]]\" (2010) makes particular reference to ''The Catcher in the Rye'' and shows that its once-controversial use of vocabulary has no impact among young readers nowadays, and pokes fun at literary critics reading deeper meaning into books. It also references its connection towards the series of high-profile assassination attempts in the 1980s, with character [[Butters Stotch]] expressing a desire to kill John Lennon after reading the book until his father tells him that Lennon was already killed.<ref>{{cite web | author=Ramsey Isler | title= South Park: \"The Tale of Scrotie McBoogerballs\" Review | work=IGN | url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2010/03/25/south-park-the-tale-of-scrotie-mcboogerballs-review | date=2010-03-25}}</ref>\n\n==Books==\n''The Catcher in the Rye'' has had significant cultural influence, and works inspired by the novel have been said to form their own genre. Sarah Graham assessed works influenced by ''The Catcher in the Rye'' to include the novels ''[[Less Than Zero (novel)|Less Than Zero]]'' by [[Bret Easton Ellis]], ''[[The Perks of Being a Wallflower]]'' by [[Stephen Chbosky]], ''[[A Complicated Kindness]]'' by [[Miriam Toews]], ''[[The Bell Jar]]'' by [[Sylvia Plath]], ''[[Ordinary People (novel)|Ordinary People]]'' by [[Judith Guest]], and the film ''[[Igby Goes Down]]'' by [[Burr Steers]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Rohrer |first=Finlo |date=June 5, 2009 |title=Why does Salinger's Catcher in the Rye still resonate? |work=BBC News Magazine |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/magazine/8084931.stm |accessdate=February 12, 2012}}</ref>\n* [[John Fowles]]'s 1963 novel ''[[The Collector]]'' uses ''The Catcher in the Rye'' as \"one of the most brilliant examples of adolescence\" in popular culture, possibly under a moral light.<ref>Whitfield, 570.</ref> In it, Miranda encourages her kidnapper Clegg to read ''Catcher'', thinking he might relate to Holden's alienation.<ref name=\"Salon\" /> However, Clegg finds Holden's actions unrealistic given Holden's wealth and status, and \"[doesn't] see much point in it.\" In the film adaptation of ''The Collector'', this conversation and Clegg's attitude toward the novel and popular culture is subdued.<ref>Whitfield, 571.</ref> The novel has itself been linked to several serial killers.<ref name=\"Salon\" />\n* [[Alberto Fuguet]]'s first novel ''[[Mala onda]]'' (''Bad Vibes'', 1991), which is set in [[Santiago, Chile]] three months before the John Lennon assassination, references ''The Catcher in the Rye'' extensively.<ref>Santini, Beno\u00eet (2013). ''Chile en el siglo XXI: \u00bfNuevos recorridos art\u00edsticos, nuevos caminos hist\u00f3ricos?''. Mago Editores.</ref> Like Holden, Mat\u00edas Vicu\u00f1a (the 17-year-old narrator and protagonist of the novel) is a cynical, alienated, upper-class teenager who feels fed-up with the blandness of his friends and family. After reading Salinger's book, Mat\u00edas feels a special connection with Holden. He attempts to replicate Holden's self-inflicted isolation by fleeing home and locking himself up in a hotel room, and he even purchases a red hunting hat to complete the persona.<ref>[[Alberto Fuguet|Fuguet, Alberto]] (1997). ''[[Mala onda|Bad Vibes]]''. [[St. Martin's Press]].</ref>\n* [[Lawrence Block]] wrote a novel called ''Burglar in the Rye'' (1999) in his series on burglar [[Bernie Rhodenbarr]]. The plot focuses on an auction of a reclusive writer's letters,<ref>{{cite news |author1=Harry Levins |author2=Susan C. Hegger |author3=Judith Evans | title=Thrillers | url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=SL&p_theme=sl&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EB0519F0B8A5A62&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D | work=[[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]] | date=1999-07-04 | accessdate=2007-05-21 | format=fee required | quote = ''Burglar in the Rye''; referring to whiskey, in a wry twist that centers on the planned auction of letters from a reclusive writer who authored a seminal...}}</ref> and Bernie works to track down the character based on J. D. Salinger.\n* In [[Galt Niederhoffer]]'s novel ''A Taxonomy of Barnacles'' (2005), Bridget and Billy think about Holden's question as to the whereabouts of ducks during winter.<ref>{{cite news | author=Ashley Simpson Shires | title='Barnacles' gets tangled | url=http://www.rockymountainnews.com/drmn/books/article/0,2792,DRMN_63_4349766,00.html | work=[[Rocky Mountain News]] | date=2005-12-30 | accessdate=2007-05-21 | quote=Niederhoffer nods to Salinger in a reference to ''The Catcher in the Rye'': Bridget and Billy pause on 72nd Street, near the Boat Pond, 'pondering Holden's question: where on earth did the ducks go during the winter months?' | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070206133118/http://www.rockymountainnews.com/drmn/books/article/0,2792,DRMN_63_4349766,00.html | archivedate=2007-02-06}}</ref>\n* [[John David California]] wrote ''60 Years Later: Coming Through the Rye'' (2009), an unauthorized sequel in which seventy-six-year-old Holden escapes a retirement home for a journey in New York.<ref>{{cite news | author=Alison Flood | title=Catcher in the Rye sequel published \u2013 but not by Salinger | url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2009/may/14/catcher-in-the-rye-sequel | work=[[The Guardian]] | date=2009-05-14}}</ref>\n* [[Bob Uecker]], a former [[Major League Baseball]] catcher named his book \"Catcher in the Wry\", a pun on the title of the Catcher in the Rye. His book recounts anecdotes of his years behind the plate and on the road, recalling the antics of his famous teammates, including Hank Aaron, Bob Gibson, Richie Allen, and Warren Spahn.\n* Fantasy writer [[Harry Turtledove]] has written a pastiche-parody \"Catcher in the Rhine\", based on his daughter's mishearing of Salinger's title. In this short story, an unnamed narrator, who is clearly meant to be Holden Caulfield but is unnamed to avoid copyright problems, goes on vacation to Germany and meets characters from the ''[[Nibelungenlied]]''. This was first published in ''[[The Chick is in the Mail]]'', edited by [[Esther Friesner]], [[Baen]] 2000 and reprinted in the omnibus ''Chicks Ahoy!'' (2010). It was reprinted in ''Atlantis and Other Places'' also in 2010.\n\n==Comic strips and Magazines==\n* The ''[[Frazz]]'' character Caulfield is named after Holden.<ref>{{cite news | author=Pat Hathcock | title=New comic strip debuts in today's Advocate | url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=VA&p_theme=va&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0FAD78EC6E0A4009&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D | work=Victoria Advocate| date=2003-05-05 | accessdate=2008-01-04}}</ref>\nThe July 1985 issue of ''[[National Lampoon (magazine)|National Lampoon]]'' included a parody of the novel, ostensibly written by Holden Caulfield's son, entitled ''The Son of the Catcher, who Lives in Rye''.\n\n==Music==\n\n* [[Night Ranger]]' 1982 song \"Night Ranger\" from their album ''[[Dawn Patrol]]'' mentions Catcher in the Rye.\nIn the heat of the night\nLooking for adventure\nOn the face of the light\nA Colorado school boy\nPut his days on the line\nNights out of paperback\n\"Catcher In The Rye\"\n\n* [[The Ataris]]' song \"If You Really Want to Hear About It\" from their album ''[[End is Forever]]'' takes its title from the novel's opening sentence. The final lines paraphrase those of the book with \"Don't ever tell anyone anything or else you'll wind up missing everybody.\" Several other specific references are made within the lyrics.<ref>{{cite news|author=Jung La |title=Ataris: End is Forever |url=http://daily.stanford.edu/article/2001/4/12/atarisEndIsForever |work=[[The Stanford Daily]] |date=2001-04-12 |accessdate=2007-06-08 |quote=The pop culture saturation of the Ataris\u2019 lyrics could get annoying if you\u2019re not into that sort of thing, but, to me, it\u2019s what makes this album stand out. \u201cIf You Really Want To Hear About It\u201d references J. D. Salinger\u2019s \u201cCatcher in the Rye\u201d... }}{{dead link|date=May 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n* [[Billy Joel]]'s \"[[We Didn't Start the Fire]]\" mentions the novel as a historic item of note during his lifetime.<ref>{{cite news | author=Chris Heim | title=Billy Joel and the `We Didn't Start the Fire' quiz | url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/chicagotribune/access/28797913.html?dids=28797913:28797913&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&date=Feb+09%2C+1990&author=Chris+Heim&pub=Chicago+Tribune+(pre-1997+Fulltext)&desc=Billy+Joel+and+the+%60We+Didn%27t+Start+the+Fire%27+quiz | work=[[Chicago Tribune]] | date=1990-02-09 | format=fee required}}</ref>\n* [[Green Day]]'s \"Who Wrote Holden Caulfield?\" from their album ''[[Kerplunk (album)|Kerplunk]]'' (1991) is named after and is about the novel's main character, [[Holden Caulfield]]. Frontman [[Billie Joe Armstrong]] recalled being forced to read the novel in high school and despising it. He later reread it as an adult, because it was seen as \"punk rock\".<ref>https://genius.com/Green-day-who-wrote-holden-caulfield-lyrics</ref>\n* [[Belle and Sebastian]]'s song \"Le Pastie De La Bourgeoisie\" from their 1997 EP ''[[3.. 6.. 9 Seconds of Light]]'' features the lyric \"Wouldn't you like to get away? Give yourself up to the allure of Catcher in the Rye, the future's swathed in stars and stripes\".\n* [[Guns and Roses]] album ''[[Chinese Democracy]]'' includes a song called [[Catcher in the Rye]] in which the narrator debates a violent fantasy.\n* Ska-Punk band [[Five Iron Frenzy]]'s song \"Superpowers\" includes the lyrics, \"I sometimes feel I'm Holden Caulfield, sometimes Jack Kerouac. I wanted to be famous, now I want to take it back.\".\n* Francesco Guccini's 1970 song \"La collina\" (The Hill) is openly inspired by this novel.\n\n==Gaming==\nThe video game ''Bully'' had the protagonist forced to attend a Connecticut boarding school. Just after being dropped off, he remarks about his mother's remarriage, calling his new stepfather a \"phony\". [[Rockstar Games]], the producer of ''Bully'', said part of the concept was inspired by ''Catcher in the Rye''.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite journal | title = Cherished and Cursed: Toward a Social History of The Catcher in the Rye | last = Whitfield | first = Stephen | journal = The New England Quarterly | volume = 70 | issue = 4 | date = December 1997 | pages = 567\u2013600 | doi = 10.2307/366646 | jstor = 366646 <!-- Article released for free download by publisher at http://www.northeastern.edu/neq/Announcements.html as per \"Free Article: A Social History of The Catcher in the Rye\", January 27, 2010 --> | url = http://www.northeastern.edu/neq/pdfs/Whitfield%2C_Stephen_J.pdf | format = PDF | accessdate = 2012-11-02  | ref = harv | url-status=dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120912144104/http://www.northeastern.edu/neq/pdfs/Whitfield%2C_Stephen_J.pdf | archivedate = September 12, 2012 | df =  | postscript = <br />. Reprinted in}} {{Cite book |title= J. D. Salinger |year=2001 |publisher= [[Chelsea House]] |location=Philadelphia |series= Bloom's BioCritiques |isbn=0-7910-6175-2 |editor1-last= Bloom |editor1-first= Harold |editor1-link= Harold Bloom | pages = 77\u2013105}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cultural references to the novel The Catcher In The Rye}}\n[[Category:Novels in popular culture|Catcher in the Rye, The]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguated:Christopher Buckley\u2192Christopher Buckley (novelist),Dawn Patrol\u2192Dawn Patrol (album)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Catcher_in_the_Rye_in_popular_culture"}
{"title_page": "Ibis", "text_new": "{{Other uses}}\n{{Automatic taxobox\n| name = Ibis\n| image = Black-headed Ibis (Threskiornis melanocephalus).jpg\n| image_caption = [[Black-headed ibis]] ''(Threskiornis melanocephalus)''\n| taxon = Threskiornithinae\n| authority = [[Franz Poche|Poche]], 1904\n| subdivision_ranks  = Genera\n| subdivision =\n*''[[Threskiornis]]''\n*''[[Pseudibis]]''\n*''[[Thaumatibis]]''\n*''[[Geronticus]]''\n*''[[Nipponia]]''\n*''[[Bostrychia]]''\n*''[[Theristicus]]''\n*''[[Cercibis]]''\n*''[[Mesembrinibis]]''\n*''[[Phimosus]]''\n*''[[Eudocimus]]''\n*''[[Plegadis]]''\n*''[[Lophotibis]]''\n}}\n\nThe '''ibises''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|a\u026a|b|\u026a|s|}}) (collective plural '''ibis''';<ref>{{cite web |title= ibis|url= http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/ibis|work= Dictionary.com Unabridged|accessdate=6 October 2009}}</ref> classical plurals '''ibides'''<ref>{{cite book |title= The Stanford dictionary of Anglicised words and phrases |editor= Fennell, C. A. M. |year= 1892 |publisher= Cambridge University Press |location= Cambridge|oclc=1354115 |page= [https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_8vRaAAAAMAAJ/page/n471 453] |url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_8vRaAAAAMAAJ |accessdate=6 October 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"morris\"/> and '''ibes'''<ref name=\"morris\">{{cite book |title= Dictionary of Hard Words |last= Pierce|first= Robert Morris|year= 1910|publisher= Dodd, Mead & Company |location= New York|oclc= 4177508|page= [https://archive.org/details/dictionaryhardw00piergoog/page/n275 270]|url= https://archive.org/details/dictionaryhardw00piergoog |accessdate=6 October 2009}}</ref>) are a group of long-legged wading [[bird]]s in the family [[Threskiornithidae]], that inhabit wetlands, forests and plains.<ref name=long>{{cite journal |last1=Longrich |first1=N. R. |last2=Olson |first2=S. L. |title=The bizarre wing of the Jamaican flightless ibis ''Xenicibis xympithecus'': a unique vertebrate adaptation |journal=Proceedings of the Royal Society B: Biological Sciences |date=5 January 2011 |volume=278 |issue=1716 |pages=2333\u20132337 |doi=10.1098/rspb.2010.2117 |pmid=21208965 |pmc=3119002}}</ref> \"Ibis\" derives from the [[Latin]] and [[Ancient Greek]] word for this group of birds. It also occurs in the scientific name of the [[cattle egret]], (''Bubulcus ibis''), mistakenly identified in 1757 as being the [[sacred ibis]].<ref name=job>{{cite book | last= Jobling | first= James A | year= 2010| title= The Helm Dictionary of Scientific Bird Names | url= https://archive.org/details/Helm_Dictionary_of_Scientific_Bird_Names_by_James_A._Jobling | publisher=Christopher Helm | location = London | isbn = 978-1-4081-2501-4 | page=[https://archive.org/details/Helm_Dictionary_of_Scientific_Bird_Names_by_James_A._Jobling/page/n201 201]}}</ref>\n\n==Description==\nIbises all have long, down-curved bills, and usually feed as a group, probing mud for food items, usually [[crustacean]]s. They are monogamous and highly territorial while nesting and feeding.<ref name=long/> Most nest in trees, often with [[spoonbill]]s or [[heron]]s. All extant species are [[Flying and gliding animals|volant]], but two extinct genera were flightless, namely the kiwi-like ''[[Apteribis]]'' in the [[Hawaiian Islands]], and the peculiar ''[[Xenicibis xympithecus|Xenicibis]]'' in [[Jamaica]].<ref name=long/> The word ''ibis'' comes from [[Latin]] ''ibis''<ref>\"ibis\". ''[[Chambers Dictionary]]''.</ref> from [[Ancient Greek|Greek]] \u1f36\u03b2\u03b9\u03c2 ''ibis'' from [[Egyptian language|Egyptian]] ''hb''<!--[sic]-->, ''h\u012bb''.<ref>[[Robert S. P. Beekes|Beekes, R. S. P.]] (2009) ''Etymological Dictionary of Greek'', Brill, p. 575. {{ISBN|9004174184}}.</ref>\n\n==Species in taxonomic order==\nThere are 28 [[extant taxon|extant]] species and 6 [[extinct]] species of ibis.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Image !! Genus   !! Living Species\n|-\n|[[File:Threskiornis molucca - Perth.jpg|175px]]||'''''[[Threskiornis]]''''' {{small|G.R. Gray, 1842}}|| \n* [[African sacred ibis]],  ''Threskiornis aethiopicus''\n* [[Malagasy sacred ibis]], ''Threskiornis bernieri''\n* [[Australian white ibis]],  ''Threskiornis mollucca/moluccus''{{#tag:ref|There is still disagreement on how the taxonomic rules should apply to the Australian white ibis, Both ''molluca'' and ''mollucus'' are currently used for species.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=David |first1=Normand |last2=Gosselin |first2=Michel |date=2011 |title=Gender agreement of avian species-group names under Article 31.2. 2 of the ICZN Code. |url= http://www.digimages.info/listeoiseauxmonde/D&G_BOC_131_2.pdf|journal= [[Bulletin of the British Ornithologists' Club]]|volume=131 |issue=2 |pages=102\u2013115 |access-date=10 August 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Schodde |first1=Richard |last2=Bock |first2=Walter |date= 2016 |title= Conflict resolution of grammar and gender for avian species-group names under Article 31.2. 2 of the ICZN Code: is gender agreement worth it?| journal=[[Zootaxa]] |volume= 4127|issue=1 |pages=161\u2013170 |doi=10.11646/zootaxa.4127.1.9 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Dickinson |first1=Edward C. |last2=David |first2=Normand |last3=Alonso-Zarazaga|first3=Miguel A. |date=2017 |title=Some comments on Schodde & Bock (2016) on gender agreement. |url=http://boc-online.org/bulletins/downloads/BBOC1372-Dickinson.pdf |journal= [[Bulletin of the British Ornithologists' Club]]|volume= 137|issue=2 |pages=142\u2013144 |access-date=10 August 2017 }}</ref>|group=\"note\"}}\n* [[Straw-necked ibis]],  ''Threskiornis spinicollis''\n* \u2020[[R\u00e9union ibis]], ''Threskiornis solitarius'' ([[extinct]])\n* [[Black-headed ibis]],  ''Threskiornis melanocephalus''\n|-\n|[[File:Indian Black Ibis Pseudibis papillosa by Dr. Raju Kasambe DSCN2445 (26).jpg|175px]]||'''''[[Pseudibis]]''''' {{small|Hodgson, 1844}}|| \n* [[Red-naped ibis]],  ''Pseudibis papillosa''\n* [[White-shouldered ibis]],  ''Pseudibis davisoni''\n* [[Giant ibis]],  ''Pseudibis gigantea''\n|-\n|[[File:Hermit Ibis in Vienna Zoo on 2013-05-14.png|175px]]||'''''[[Geronticus]]''''' {{small|Wagler, 1832}}|| \n* [[Northern bald ibis]],  ''Geronticus eremita''\n* [[Southern bald ibis]],  ''Geronticus calvus''\n|-\n|[[File:Nipponia nippon.jpg|175px]]||'''''[[Nipponia]]''''' {{small|Reichenbach, 1850}}|| \n* [[Crested ibis]],  ''Nipponia nippon ''\n|-\n|[[File:Hadeda Ibis Portrait.jpg|175px]]||'''''[[Bostrychia]]''''' {{small|G.R. Gray, 1847}}|| \n* [[Olive ibis]],  ''Bostrychia olivacea''\n* [[S\u00e3o Tom\u00e9 ibis]], ''Bostrychia bocagei''\n* [[Spot-breasted ibis]],  ''Bostrychia rara''\n* [[Hadada ibis]],  ''Bostrychia hagedash''\n* [[Wattled ibis]],  ''Bostrychia carunculata''\n|-\n|[[File:Wildlife in and around Reserva Laguna Nimez in El Calafate, Argentina - there is some uncertainty here amongst some authorities- is this the Black Faced Ibis (Theristicus melanops) - OR - the (24560030193).jpg|175px]]||'''''[[Theristicus]]''''' {{small|Wagler, 1832}}|| \n* [[Plumbeous ibis]], ''Theristicus caerulescens''\n* [[Buff-necked ibis]], ''Theristicus caudatus''\n* [[Black-faced ibis]], ''Theristicus melanopis''\n* [[Andean ibis]], ''Theristicus branickii''\n|-\n|[[File:Cercibis oxycerca Tarotaro Sharp-tailed Ibis (6288776691).jpg|175px]]||'''''[[Cercibis]]''''' {{small|Wagler, 1832}}|| \n* [[Sharp-tailed ibis]],  ''Cercibis oxycerca''\n|-\n|[[File:Green Ibis (Mesembrinibis cayennensis) (30903118634).jpg|175px]]||'''''[[Mesembrinibis]]''''' {{small|J.L. Peters, 1930}}|| \n* [[Green ibis]],  ''Mesembrinibis cayennensis''\n|-\n|[[File:Bare-faced Ibis (Phimosus infuscatus) (28370845522).jpg|175px]]||'''''[[Phimosus]]''''' {{small|Wagler, 1832}}|| \n* [[Bare-faced ibis]],  ''Phimosus infuscatus''\n|-\n|[[File:Eudocimus Ruber Wading KL.JPG|175px]]||'''''[[Eudocimus]]''''' {{small|Wagler, 1832}}|| \n* [[American white ibis]],  ''Eudocimus albus''\n* [[Scarlet ibis]],  ''Eudocimus ruber''\n|-\n|[[File:Plegadis chihi -California, USA-8.jpg|175px]]||'''''[[Plegadis]]''''' {{small|Kaup, 1829}}|| \n* [[Glossy ibis]],  ''Plegadis falcinellus''\n* [[White-faced ibis]],  ''Plegadis chihi''\n* [[Puna ibis]],  ''Plegadis ridgwayi''\n|-\n|[[File:Lophotibis cristata -Bronx Zoo-8.jpg|175px]]||'''''[[Lophotibis]]''''' {{small|L. Reichenbach, 1853}}|| \n* [[Madagascar ibis]],  ''Lophotibis cristata''\n|-\n|[[File:Apteribis sp. (5212794163).jpg|175px]]||\u2020 '''''[[Apteribis]]''''' {{small|Olson & Wetmore, 1976}}|| \n* \u2020''[[Moloka'i flightless ibis|A. glenos]]'' <small>Olson & Wetmore, 1976</small> Molokai flightless ibis\n* \u2020''[[Maui flightless ibis|A. brevis]]'' <small>Olson & James, 1991</small> Maui flightless ibis\n|-\n|}\n\nAn extinct species, the [[Jamaican ibis]] or clubbed-wing ibis (''Xenicibis xympithecus'') was uniquely characterized by its club-like wings.\n\n==In culture==\nThe [[African sacred ibis]] was an object of religious [[veneration]] in [[ancient Egypt]], particularly associated with the deity [[Djehuty]] or otherwise commonly referred to in Greek as [[Thoth]]. He is responsible for writing, mathematics, measurement and time as well as the moon and magic.<ref name=BMA>{{cite book|last=[[Birmingham Museum of Art]]|title=Birmingham Museum of Art : guide to the collection|year=2010|publisher=Birmingham Museum of Art|isbn=978-1-904832-77-5|page=65|url=http://www.artsbma.org/pieces/ibis/}}</ref> In artworks of the [[Late Period of Ancient Egypt]], Thoth is popularly depicted as an ibis-headed man in the act of writing.<ref name=\"BMA\"/> However, [[Mitogenomic]] diversity in sacred ibis mummies indicate that ancient Egyptians captured the birds from the wild rather than farming them.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Wasef|first1=Sally|last2=Subramanian|first2=Sankar|last3=O\u2019Rorke|first3=Richard|last4=Huynen|first4=Leon|last5=El-Marghani|first5=Samia|last6=Curtis|first6=Caitlin|last7=Popinga|first7=Alex|last8=Holland|first8=Barbara|last9=Ikram|first9=Salima|last10=Millar|first10=Craig|last11=Willerslev|first11=Eske|last12=Lambert|first12=David|title=Mitogenomic diversity in Sacred Ibis Mummies sheds light on early Egyptian practices|publisher=PLoS ONE|year=2019|volume=14|issue=11|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0223964}}</ref>\n\nAt the town of [[Hermopolis]], ibises were reared specifically for sacrificial purposes and in the [[serapeum]] at [[Saqqara]], archaeologists found the mummies of one and a half million ibises and hundreds of thousands of [[falcon]]s.<ref>Fleming, Furgus; Alan Lothian (1997) [https://archive.org/details/waytoeternityegy00flem ''The Way to Eternity: Egyptian Myth'']. Amsterdam: Time-Life Books. pp. 66\u201367</ref>\n\nAccording to local legend in the [[Birecik]] area, the [[northern bald ibis]] was one of the first birds that [[Noah]] released from the Ark as a symbol of fertility,<ref name= Shuker>{{cite book | last = Shuker | first = Karl | title = The Beasts That Hide from Man: Seeking the World's Last Undiscovered Animals | year = 2003 | pages = 166\u2013168 |publisher  = Cosimo| isbn =1-931044-64-3 }} \"Dreams of a feathered ''Geronticus''\"</ref> and a lingering religious sentiment in Turkey helped the colonies there to survive long after the demise of the species in Europe.<ref name=aewa6>{{cite web | author = Beintema, Nienke | title = Saving a charismatic bird | url = http://www.unep-aewa.org/publications/saving_charismatic_bird.pdf | format = PDF | publisher = AEWA Secretariat | accessdate = 11 December 2008 | url-status = bot: unknown | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120301224158/http://www.unep-aewa.org/publications/saving_charismatic_bird.pdf | archivedate = 1 March 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2019/11/191113153104.htm|title=Ancient Egyptians gathered birds from the wild for sacrifice and mummification: DNA study rejects the idea that Egyptians domesticated sacred ibis for ritual use|website=ScienceDaily|language=en|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref>\n\nThe mascot of the [[University of Miami]] is an [[American white ibis]] named [[Sebastian the Ibis|Sebastian]].  The ibis was selected as the school mascot because of its legendary bravery during hurricanes.  According to legend, the ibis is the last sign of wildlife to take shelter before a hurricane hits and the first to reappear once the storm has passed.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20110519081217/http://hurricanesports.cstv.com/trads/mifl-mascot.html Sebastian the Ibis]. Hurricane sports</ref>\n\n{{anchor|lampoon}}\n[[Harvard University]]'s humor magazine, ''[[Harvard Lampoon]]'', uses the ibis as its symbol. A copper statue of an ibis is prominently displayed on the roof of the [[Harvard Lampoon Building]] at 44 Bow Street.\n\nA short story \"[[The Scarlet Ibis]]\" by James Hurst uses the red bird as foreshadowing for a character's death and as the primary symbol.\n\nThe [[African sacred ibis]] is the unit symbol of the [[Israeli Special Forces]] unit known as Unit 212 or [[Maglan]] (Hebrew \u05de\u05d2\u05dc\u05df).\n\nAccording to Josephus, Moses used the ibis to help him defeat the Ethiopians.<ref>Josephus. [http://penelope.uchicago.edu/josephus/ant-2.html ''Antiquities of the Jews'']. 2.10.</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Black-headed Ibis (Threskiornis melanocephalus).jpg|[[Black-headed ibis]]\nFile:AustralianWhiteIbis gobeirne.jpg|[[Australian white ibis]]\nFile:American white ibis2.jpg|[[American white ibis]]\nFile:Scarletibis tj.jpg|[[Scarlet ibis]]\nFile:Black Ibis- Hodal I IMG 9701.jpg|[[Black ibis]]\nFile:Threskiornis spinicollis-fragment.jpg|[[Straw-necked ibis]]\nFile:Glossy Ibis (Plegadis falcinellus) in AP W IMG 3918.jpg|[[Glossy ibis]]\nFile:Waldrapp Geronticus eremita.jpg|[[Northern bald ibis]]\nFile:Hadada ibis, South Africa (2017).jpg|[[Hadada ibis]]\n</gallery>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=\"note\"}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n<!--\nhttp://www.funpecrp.com.br/gmr/year2013/vol12-3/pdf/gmr2779.pdf Molecular phylogeny of Threskiornithidae (Aves: Pelecaniformes) based on nuclear and mitochondrial DNA\n-->\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Pseudibis}}\n*[http://ibc.lynxeds.com/family/ibises-spoonbills-threskiornithidae Ibis videos] \u2013 at Internet Bird Collection\n*{{Cite NIE|wstitle=Ibis |year=1905 |short=x}}\n{{Wiktionary-inline|ibis}}\n\n{{Threskiornithidae}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q193833}}\n\n[[Category:Ibises| ]]\n[[Category:Threskiornithidae]]\n\ntrash bird\n", "text_old": "{{Other uses}}\n{{Automatic taxobox\n| name = Ibis\n| image = Black-headed Ibis (Threskiornis melanocephalus).jpg\n| image_caption = [[Black-headed ibis]] ''(Threskiornis melanocephalus)''\n| taxon = Threskiornithinae\n| authority = [[Franz Poche|Poche]], 1904\n| subdivision_ranks  = Genera\n| subdivision =\n*''[[Threskiornis]]''\n*''[[Pseudibis]]''\n*''[[Thaumatibis]]''\n*''[[Geronticus]]''\n*''[[Nipponia]]''\n*''[[Bostrychia]]''\n*''[[Theristicus]]''\n*''[[Cercibis]]''\n*''[[Mesembrinibis]]''\n*''[[Phimosus]]''\n*''[[Eudocimus]]''\n*''[[Plegadis]]''\n*''[[Lophotibis]]''\n}}\n\nThe '''ibises''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|a\u026a|b|\u026a|s|}}) (collective plural '''ibis''';<ref>{{cite web |title= ibis|url= http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/ibis|work= Dictionary.com Unabridged|accessdate=6 October 2009}}</ref> classical plurals '''ibides'''<ref>{{cite book |title= The Stanford dictionary of Anglicised words and phrases |editor= Fennell, C. A. M. |year= 1892 |publisher= Cambridge University Press |location= Cambridge|oclc=1354115 |page= [https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_8vRaAAAAMAAJ/page/n471 453] |url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_8vRaAAAAMAAJ |accessdate=6 October 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"morris\"/> and '''ibes'''<ref name=\"morris\">{{cite book |title= Dictionary of Hard Words |last= Pierce|first= Robert Morris|year= 1910|publisher= Dodd, Mead & Company |location= New York|oclc= 4177508|page= [https://archive.org/details/dictionaryhardw00piergoog/page/n275 270]|url= https://archive.org/details/dictionaryhardw00piergoog |accessdate=6 October 2009}}</ref>) are a group of long-legged wading [[bird]]s in the family [[Threskiornithidae]], that inhabit wetlands, forests and plains.<ref name=long>{{cite journal |last1=Longrich |first1=N. R. |last2=Olson |first2=S. L. |title=The bizarre wing of the Jamaican flightless ibis ''Xenicibis xympithecus'': a unique vertebrate adaptation |journal=Proceedings of the Royal Society B: Biological Sciences |date=5 January 2011 |volume=278 |issue=1716 |pages=2333\u20132337 |doi=10.1098/rspb.2010.2117 |pmid=21208965 |pmc=3119002}}</ref> \"Ibis\" derives from the [[Latin]] and [[Ancient Greek]] word for this group of birds. It also occurs in the scientific name of the [[cattle egret]], (''Bubulcus ibis''), mistakenly identified in 1757 as being the [[sacred ibis]].<ref name=job>{{cite book | last= Jobling | first= James A | year= 2010| title= The Helm Dictionary of Scientific Bird Names | url= https://archive.org/details/Helm_Dictionary_of_Scientific_Bird_Names_by_James_A._Jobling | publisher=Christopher Helm | location = London | isbn = 978-1-4081-2501-4 | page=[https://archive.org/details/Helm_Dictionary_of_Scientific_Bird_Names_by_James_A._Jobling/page/n201 201]}}</ref>\n\n==Description==\nIbises all have long, down-curved bills, and usually feed as a group, probing mud for food items, usually [[crustacean]]s. They are monogamous and highly territorial while nesting and feeding.<ref name=long/> Most nest in trees, often with [[spoonbill]]s or [[heron]]s. All extant species are [[Flying and gliding animals|volant]], but two extinct genera were flightless, namely the kiwi-like ''[[Apteribis]]'' in the [[Hawaiian Islands]], and the peculiar ''[[Xenicibis xympithecus|Xenicibis]]'' in [[Jamaica]].<ref name=long/> The word ''ibis'' comes from [[Latin]] ''ibis''<ref>\"ibis\". ''[[Chambers Dictionary]]''.</ref> from [[Ancient Greek|Greek]] \u1f36\u03b2\u03b9\u03c2 ''ibis'' from [[Egyptian language|Egyptian]] ''hb''<!--[sic]-->, ''h\u012bb''.<ref>[[Robert S. P. Beekes|Beekes, R. S. P.]] (2009) ''Etymological Dictionary of Greek'', Brill, p. 575. {{ISBN|9004174184}}.</ref>\n\n==Species in taxonomic order==\nThere are 28 [[extant taxon|extant]] species and 6 [[extinct]] species of ibis.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Image !! Genus   !! Living Species\n|-\n|[[File:Threskiornis molucca - Perth.jpg|175px]]||'''''[[Threskiornis]]''''' {{small|G.R. Gray, 1842}}|| \n* [[African sacred ibis]],  ''Threskiornis aethiopicus''\n* [[Malagasy sacred ibis]], ''Threskiornis bernieri''\n* [[Australian white ibis]],  ''Threskiornis mollucca/moluccus''{{#tag:ref|There is still disagreement on how the taxonomic rules should apply to the Australian white ibis, Both ''molluca'' and ''mollucus'' are currently used for species.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=David |first1=Normand |last2=Gosselin |first2=Michel |date=2011 |title=Gender agreement of avian species-group names under Article 31.2. 2 of the ICZN Code. |url= http://www.digimages.info/listeoiseauxmonde/D&G_BOC_131_2.pdf|journal= [[Bulletin of the British Ornithologists' Club]]|volume=131 |issue=2 |pages=102\u2013115 |access-date=10 August 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Schodde |first1=Richard |last2=Bock |first2=Walter |date= 2016 |title= Conflict resolution of grammar and gender for avian species-group names under Article 31.2. 2 of the ICZN Code: is gender agreement worth it?| journal=[[Zootaxa]] |volume= 4127|issue=1 |pages=161\u2013170 |doi=10.11646/zootaxa.4127.1.9 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Dickinson |first1=Edward C. |last2=David |first2=Normand |last3=Alonso-Zarazaga|first3=Miguel A. |date=2017 |title=Some comments on Schodde & Bock (2016) on gender agreement. |url=http://boc-online.org/bulletins/downloads/BBOC1372-Dickinson.pdf |journal= [[Bulletin of the British Ornithologists' Club]]|volume= 137|issue=2 |pages=142\u2013144 |access-date=10 August 2017 }}</ref>|group=\"note\"}}\n* [[Straw-necked ibis]],  ''Threskiornis spinicollis''\n* \u2020[[R\u00e9union ibis]], ''Threskiornis solitarius'' ([[extinct]])\n* [[Black-headed ibis]],  ''Threskiornis melanocephalus''\n|-\n|[[File:Indian Black Ibis Pseudibis papillosa by Dr. Raju Kasambe DSCN2445 (26).jpg|175px]]||'''''[[Pseudibis]]''''' {{small|Hodgson, 1844}}|| \n* [[Red-naped ibis]],  ''Pseudibis papillosa''\n* [[White-shouldered ibis]],  ''Pseudibis davisoni''\n* [[Giant ibis]],  ''Pseudibis gigantea''\n|-\n|[[File:Hermit Ibis in Vienna Zoo on 2013-05-14.png|175px]]||'''''[[Geronticus]]''''' {{small|Wagler, 1832}}|| \n* [[Northern bald ibis]],  ''Geronticus eremita''\n* [[Southern bald ibis]],  ''Geronticus calvus''\n|-\n|[[File:Nipponia nippon.jpg|175px]]||'''''[[Nipponia]]''''' {{small|Reichenbach, 1850}}|| \n* [[Crested ibis]],  ''Nipponia nippon ''\n|-\n|[[File:Hadeda Ibis Portrait.jpg|175px]]||'''''[[Bostrychia]]''''' {{small|G.R. Gray, 1847}}|| \n* [[Olive ibis]],  ''Bostrychia olivacea''\n* [[S\u00e3o Tom\u00e9 ibis]], ''Bostrychia bocagei''\n* [[Spot-breasted ibis]],  ''Bostrychia rara''\n* [[Hadada ibis]],  ''Bostrychia hagedash''\n* [[Wattled ibis]],  ''Bostrychia carunculata''\n|-\n|[[File:Wildlife in and around Reserva Laguna Nimez in El Calafate, Argentina - there is some uncertainty here amongst some authorities- is this the Black Faced Ibis (Theristicus melanops) - OR - the (24560030193).jpg|175px]]||'''''[[Theristicus]]''''' {{small|Wagler, 1832}}|| \n* [[Plumbeous ibis]], ''Theristicus caerulescens''\n* [[Buff-necked ibis]], ''Theristicus caudatus''\n* [[Black-faced ibis]], ''Theristicus melanopis''\n* [[Andean ibis]], ''Theristicus branickii''\n|-\n|[[File:Cercibis oxycerca Tarotaro Sharp-tailed Ibis (6288776691).jpg|175px]]||'''''[[Cercibis]]''''' {{small|Wagler, 1832}}|| \n* [[Sharp-tailed ibis]],  ''Cercibis oxycerca''\n|-\n|[[File:Green Ibis (Mesembrinibis cayennensis) (30903118634).jpg|175px]]||'''''[[Mesembrinibis]]''''' {{small|J.L. Peters, 1930}}|| \n* [[Green ibis]],  ''Mesembrinibis cayennensis''\n|-\n|[[File:Bare-faced Ibis (Phimosus infuscatus) (28370845522).jpg|175px]]||'''''[[Phimosus]]''''' {{small|Wagler, 1832}}|| \n* [[Bare-faced ibis]],  ''Phimosus infuscatus''\n|-\n|[[File:Eudocimus Ruber Wading KL.JPG|175px]]||'''''[[Eudocimus]]''''' {{small|Wagler, 1832}}|| \n* [[American white ibis]],  ''Eudocimus albus''\n* [[Scarlet ibis]],  ''Eudocimus ruber''\n|-\n|[[File:Plegadis chihi -California, USA-8.jpg|175px]]||'''''[[Plegadis]]''''' {{small|Kaup, 1829}}|| \n* [[Glossy ibis]],  ''Plegadis falcinellus''\n* [[White-faced ibis]],  ''Plegadis chihi''\n* [[Puna ibis]],  ''Plegadis ridgwayi''\n|-\n|[[File:Lophotibis cristata -Bronx Zoo-8.jpg|175px]]||'''''[[Lophotibis]]''''' {{small|L. Reichenbach, 1853}}|| \n* [[Madagascar ibis]],  ''Lophotibis cristata''\n|-\n|[[File:Apteribis sp. (5212794163).jpg|175px]]||\u2020 '''''[[Apteribis]]''''' {{small|Olson & Wetmore, 1976}}|| \n* \u2020''[[Moloka'i flightless ibis|A. glenos]]'' <small>Olson & Wetmore, 1976</small> Molokai flightless ibis\n* \u2020''[[Maui flightless ibis|A. brevis]]'' <small>Olson & James, 1991</small> Maui flightless ibis\n|-\n|}\n\nAn extinct species, the [[Jamaican ibis]] or clubbed-wing ibis (''Xenicibis xympithecus'') was uniquely characterized by its club-like wings.\n\n==In culture==\nThe [[African sacred ibis]] was an object of religious [[veneration]] in [[ancient Egypt]], particularly associated with the deity [[Djehuty]] or otherwise commonly referred to in Greek as [[Thoth]]. He is responsible for writing, mathematics, measurement and time as well as the moon and magic.<ref name=BMA>{{cite book|last=[[Birmingham Museum of Art]]|title=Birmingham Museum of Art : guide to the collection|year=2010|publisher=Birmingham Museum of Art|isbn=978-1-904832-77-5|page=65|url=http://www.artsbma.org/pieces/ibis/}}</ref> In artworks of the [[Late Period of Ancient Egypt]], Thoth is popularly depicted as an ibis-headed man in the act of writing.<ref name=\"BMA\"/> However, [[Mitogenomic]] diversity in sacred ibis mummies indicate that ancient Egyptians captured the birds from the wild rather than farming them.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Wasef|first1=Sally|last2=Subramanian|first2=Sankar|last3=O\u2019Rorke|first3=Richard|last4=Huynen|first4=Leon|last5=El-Marghani|first5=Samia|last6=Curtis|first6=Caitlin|last7=Popinga|first7=Alex|last8=Holland|first8=Barbara|last9=Ikram|first9=Salima|last10=Millar|first10=Craig|last11=Willerslev|first11=Eske|last12=Lambert|first12=David|title=Mitogenomic diversity in Sacred Ibis Mummies sheds light on early Egyptian practices|publisher=PLoS ONE|year=2019|volume=14|issue=11|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0223964}}</ref>\n\nAt the town of [[Hermopolis]], ibises were reared specifically for sacrificial purposes and in the [[serapeum]] at [[Saqqara]], archaeologists found the mummies of one and a half million ibises and hundreds of thousands of [[falcon]]s.<ref>Fleming, Furgus; Alan Lothian (1997) [https://archive.org/details/waytoeternityegy00flem ''The Way to Eternity: Egyptian Myth'']. Amsterdam: Time-Life Books. pp. 66\u201367</ref>\n\nAccording to local legend in the [[Birecik]] area, the [[northern bald ibis]] was one of the first birds that [[Noah]] released from the Ark as a symbol of fertility,<ref name= Shuker>{{cite book | last = Shuker | first = Karl | title = The Beasts That Hide from Man: Seeking the World's Last Undiscovered Animals | year = 2003 | pages = 166\u2013168 |publisher  = Cosimo| isbn =1-931044-64-3 }} \"Dreams of a feathered ''Geronticus''\"</ref> and a lingering religious sentiment in Turkey helped the colonies there to survive long after the demise of the species in Europe.<ref name=aewa6>{{cite web | author = Beintema, Nienke | title = Saving a charismatic bird | url = http://www.unep-aewa.org/publications/saving_charismatic_bird.pdf | format = PDF | publisher = AEWA Secretariat | accessdate = 11 December 2008 | url-status = bot: unknown | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120301224158/http://www.unep-aewa.org/publications/saving_charismatic_bird.pdf | archivedate = 1 March 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2019/11/191113153104.htm|title=Ancient Egyptians gathered birds from the wild for sacrifice and mummification: DNA study rejects the idea that Egyptians domesticated sacred ibis for ritual use|website=ScienceDaily|language=en|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref>\n\nThe mascot of the [[University of Miami]] is an [[American white ibis]] named [[Sebastian the Ibis|Sebastian]].  The ibis was selected as the school mascot because of its legendary bravery during hurricanes.  According to legend, the ibis is the last sign of wildlife to take shelter before a hurricane hits and the first to reappear once the storm has passed.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20110519081217/http://hurricanesports.cstv.com/trads/mifl-mascot.html Sebastian the Ibis]. Hurricane sports</ref>\n\n{{anchor|lampoon}}\n[[Harvard University]]'s humor magazine, ''[[Harvard Lampoon]]'', uses the ibis as its symbol. A copper statue of an ibis is prominently displayed on the roof of the [[Harvard Lampoon Building]] at 44 Bow Street.\n\nA short story \"[[The Scarlet Ibis]]\" by James Hurst uses the red bird as foreshadowing for a character's death and as the primary symbol.\n\nThe [[African sacred ibis]] is the unit symbol of the [[Israeli Special Forces]] unit known as Unit 212 or [[Maglan]] (Hebrew \u05de\u05d2\u05dc\u05df).\n\nAccording to Josephus, Moses used the ibis to help him defeat the Ethiopians.<ref>Josephus. [http://penelope.uchicago.edu/josephus/ant-2.html ''Antiquities of the Jews'']. 2.10.</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Black-headed Ibis (Threskiornis melanocephalus).jpg|[[Black-headed ibis]]\nFile:AustralianWhiteIbis gobeirne.jpg|[[Australian white ibis]]\nFile:American white ibis2.jpg|[[American white ibis]]\nFile:Scarletibis tj.jpg|[[Scarlet ibis]]\nFile:Black Ibis- Hodal I IMG 9701.jpg|[[Black ibis]]\nFile:Threskiornis spinicollis-fragment.jpg|[[Straw-necked ibis]]\nFile:Glossy Ibis (Plegadis falcinellus) in AP W IMG 3918.jpg|[[Glossy ibis]]\nFile:Waldrapp Geronticus eremita.jpg|[[Northern bald ibis]]\nFile:Hadada ibis, South Africa (2017).jpg|[[Hadada ibis]]\n</gallery>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=\"note\"}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n<!--\nhttp://www.funpecrp.com.br/gmr/year2013/vol12-3/pdf/gmr2779.pdf Molecular phylogeny of Threskiornithidae (Aves: Pelecaniformes) based on nuclear and mitochondrial DNA\n-->\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Pseudibis}}\n*[http://ibc.lynxeds.com/family/ibises-spoonbills-threskiornithidae Ibis videos] \u2013 at Internet Bird Collection\n*{{Cite NIE|wstitle=Ibis |year=1905 |short=x}}\n{{Wiktionary-inline|ibis}}\n\n{{Threskiornithidae}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q193833}}\n\n[[Category:Ibises| ]]\n[[Category:Threskiornithidae]]\n", "name_user": "87.199.45.36", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ibis"}
{"title_page": "Olivia Cooke", "text_new": "{{short description|English actress}}\n{{EngvarB|date=March 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Olivia Cooke\n| image        = Olivia Cooke by Gage Skidmore 2.jpg\n| caption      = Cooke at the 2018 [[WonderCon]]\n| birth_name   = Olivia Kate Cooke\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|1993|12|27|Age 26}}\n| birth_place  = [[Oldham]], England\n| residence    = [[New York City]], U.S.\n| occupation   = Actress\n| years_active = 2012\u2013present\n}}\n\n'''Olivia Kate Cooke'''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:QVH9-6K2H|title=Person Details for Olivia Kate Cooke, \"England and Wales Birth Registration Index, 1837\u20132008\"|website=[[FamilySearch]]|access-date=6 December 2015}}</ref> (born 27 December 1993) is an English actress. She is known for her starring role as [[List of Bates Motel characters#Emma Decody|Emma Decody]] in the [[A&E (TV channel)|A&E]] drama thriller series ''[[Bates Motel (TV series)|Bates Motel]]'' (2013\u20132017) and as [[Becky Sharp]] in the period drama [[miniseries]] ''[[Vanity Fair (2018 TV series)|Vanity Fair]]'' (2018). \n\nCooke has also starred in the horror film ''[[Ouija (2014 film)|Ouija]]'' (2014), the comedy-drama film ''[[Me and Earl and the Dying Girl (film)|Me and Earl and the Dying Girl]]'' (2015), the period horror mystery film ''[[The Limehouse Golem]]'' (2016), the thriller film ''[[Thoroughbreds (2017 film)|Thoroughbreds]]'' (2017), and the [[Steven Spielberg]]\u2013directed science fiction film ''[[Ready Player One (film)|Ready Player One]]'' (2018).\n\n==Early life==\nCooke was born and raised in [[Oldham]], [[Greater Manchester]]. Her father, John Cooke, is a retired police officer, and her mother, Lindsy Wild, is a sales representative. She has one younger sister.<ref name=interview>{{cite web|url=http://www.interviewmagazine.com/culture/discovery-olivia-cooke|title=Discovery: Olivia Cooke|first=Emma|last=Brown|website=[[Interview (magazine)|Interview]]|access-date=9 May 2014}}</ref><ref name=chronicle>{{cite web|url=http://www.oldham-chronicle.co.uk/news-features/8/news/75418/secrets-out-olivia-a-rising-star-in-uk-and-us|title=Secret's out: Olivia a rising star in UK and US|date=21 November 2012|website=[[Oldham Evening Chronicle]]|access-date=21 August 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140821180754/http://www.oldham-chronicle.co.uk/news-features/8/news/75418/secrets-out-olivia-a-rising-star-in-uk-and-us|archivedate=21 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oldhamathletic.co.uk/news/article/20130612-safetyofficer-861080.aspx|title=Latics' new safety officer|website=Oldham Athletic|date=12 June 2013|access-date=13 December 2015}}</ref> When Cooke was a child, her parents divorced, and she and her younger sister lived with their mother.<ref name=thestar>{{cite web|last=Barnard|first=Linda|title=Three questions for Thomas Mann, RJ Cyler, Olivia Cooke, stars of Me and Earl and the Dying Girl|url=https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/movies/2015/06/08/three-questions-for-thomas-mann-rj-cyler-olivia-cooke-stars-of-me-and-earl-and-the-dying-girl.html|date=8 June 2015|website=[[Toronto Star]]}}</ref> Cooke attended [[Royton and Crompton School|Royton and Crompton Academy]] and studied drama at [[Oldham Sixth Form College]], leaving before the end of her [[A-levels]] to appear in ''[[Blackout (TV series)|Blackout]]''.<ref name=chronicle/>\n\nCooke started acting when she was 8 years old at an after-school drama programme in her hometown, called the [[Oldham Theatre Workshop]]. At 17, when she starred as [[Maria (West Side Story)|Maria]] alongside Tomas Manchester in Oldham Sixth Form College's production of ''[[West Side Story]]''. Soon after, Cooke landed her first and last leading role for the Oldham Theatre Workshop, in ''Prom: The Musical'', a remake of ''[[Cinderella]]''.<ref name=interview/><ref name=chronicle/>\n\nWhen she was 14, Cooke secured her first local talent agent in [[Manchester]], who placed her in a number of commercials.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://voices.suntimes.com/arts-entertainment/the-daily-sizzle/the-quiet-ones-star-olivia-cooke-i-have-no-dignity-anymore-after-this-movie/#.U2e_FnrD8m8|title='The Quiet Ones' star Olivia Cooke: 'I have no dignity anymore after this movie.'|last=Pearlman|first=Cindy|website=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|date=23 April 2014|accessdate=9 May 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141218065158/http://voices.suntimes.com/arts-entertainment/the-daily-sizzle/the-quiet-ones-star-olivia-cooke-i-have-no-dignity-anymore-after-this-movie/#.U2e_FnrD8m8|archivedate=18 December 2014}}</ref> In 2012, she appeared in [[One Direction]]'s \"Autumn Term\" tour video, as a student getting a piggyback ride from [[Harry Styles]].<ref name=teenvogue>{{cite web|url=http://www.teenvogue.com/entertainment/movies/2014-03/olivia-cooke/?slide=1|title=Meet Olivia Cooke, the Scary-Good Actress Set to Take Hollywood by Storm|last=Rotunno|first=Anthony|website=[[Teen Vogue]]|access-date=9 May 2014}}</ref>Although Cooke's agent discouraged her from enrolling in drama school because she was already getting acting work, Cooke was keen on applying to the [[Royal Academy of Dramatic Art]] (RADA). She made it to the final round of auditions, but was not accepted.<ref name=interview/>\n\n==Career==\n\n===2012\u20132013: Career beginnings===\nAfter Cooke performed at the Oldham Theatre Workshop, Beverley Keogh, a casting director next door to her agency, secured her roles in television. Cooke starred in two [[BBC]] miniseries productions in 2012: ''[[Blackout (TV series)|Blackout]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://chrisecclestonbulletin.blogspot.com/2011/05/fuse.html?m=1|title='Blackout'|website=Art Thou Beguil'd Now? Chris Eccleston Bulletin|access-date=9 May 2014}}</ref> as the daughter of [[Christopher Eccleston]]'s character, and ''[[The Secret of Crickley Hall (TV series)|The Secret of Crickley Hall]]'', as a young teacher at a tyrannical orphanage in the 1940s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/news/a407099/psycho-tv-prequel-bates-motel-adds-blackout-star-olivia-cooke.html|title='Psycho' TV prequel 'Bates Motel' adds 'Blackout' star Olivia Cooke|last=Jeffery|first=Morgan|website=[[Digital Spy]]|date=20 September 2012|access-date=30 September 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aetv.com/bates-motel/cast/olivia-cooke|title=Meet the Cast: Olivia Cooke as Emma Decody|website=[[Bates Motel (TV series)|Bates Motel]]. AETV.com|access-date=9 May 2014}}</ref> Cooke stated that she felt better suited for television than theatre, as she was embarrassed by the exaggerated gestures sometimes required for stage acting.<ref name=interview/> Despite being a novice, Cooke distinguished herself among European actresses in the gruelling casting process for ''[[The Quiet Ones (2014 film)|The Quiet Ones]]'', which opened in April 2014, two years after filming took place.<ref name=diy>{{cite web|url=http://www.thisisfakediy.co.uk/mobile/articles/film/interview-olivia-cooke/|title=Interview: Olivia Cooke|date=9 April 2014|website=[[This Is Fake DIY|DIY]] Film|access-date=9 May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The Quiet Ones World Premiere|url=http://www.thelondonfilmreview.com/even/quiet-ones-world-premiere/|website=The London Film Review|access-date=22 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, following ''The Quiet Ones'', Cooke acquired an agent in [[Los Angeles]].<ref name=collider/> After reading the character descriptions for [[A&E (TV channel)|A&E]]'s contemporary ''[[Psycho (1960 film)|Psycho]]'' prequel ''[[Bates Motel (TV series)|Bates Motel]]'', she sent an audition tape for the role of Emma Decody.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://zap2it.com/blogs/bates_motels_olivia_cooke_im_not_sexy_so_ill_go_for_emma-2013-04|title='Bates Motel's' Olivia Cooke: 'I'm not sexy, so I'll go for Emma'|last=O'Hare|first=Kate|website=[[Zap2It]]|date=8 April 2013|access-date=30 September 2013}}</ref> Three weeks later, Cooke earned the part of Emma, her first American role.<ref name=collider>{{cite web|url=http://www.collider.com/nicola-peltz-olivia-cooke-bates-motel-interview/|title=Nicola Peltz and Olivia Cooke Talk BATES MOTEL, Their Characters, Their Familiarity with PSYCHO, and More|last=Radish|first=Christina|website=[[Collider (website)|Collider]]|access-date=30 September 2013}}</ref> She was originally disappointed when the producers made Emma [[Manchester|Mancunian]], believing it was a fail-safe measure regarding her accent. However, aided by fellow English actor [[Freddie Highmore]], who has previous experience with an American accent, Cooke has since been mistaken to be American.<ref name=interview/><ref>{{cite web|title=Bates Motel: Olivia Cooke Is Not American|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UqBFjXN9-mY|website=[[A&E (TV channel)|A&E]]. [[YouTube]]|date=7 May 2014|access-date=22 May 2014}}</ref> Cooke also contributed short videos for Emma's fictitious [[blog]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aetv.com/bates-motel/emmas-blog/|title=Emma's Blog: My Life in Fast-Forward|website=[[Bates Motel (TV series)|Bates Motel]]. AETV.com|access-date=9 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n===2014\u2013present: Further success===\n[[File:Olivia Cooke SDCC2017.jpg|thumb|upright|Cooke speaking at the 2017 [[San Diego Comic-Con]]]]\nCooke's second feature film ''[[The Signal (2014 film)|The Signal]]'', with [[Brenton Thwaites]] and [[Laurence Fishburne]], opened at the [[2014 Sundance Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Sundance 2014: Park City at Midnight|url=http://www.indiewire.com/article/sundance-2014-park-city-at-midnight|website=[[Indiewire]]|date=10 January 2014}}</ref> Cooke starred as Haley Peterson, an American [[MIT]] student transferring to [[Caltech]], who encounters strange occurrences as she, her boyfriend, and her best friend are lured into the desert by a hacker. In October 2014, Cooke led the cast of ''[[Ouija (2014 film)|Ouija]]'', a horror film based on [[Hasbro]]'s board game.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.comingsoon.net/news/movienews.php?id=114202|title=Universal Dates Crimson Peak, Ouija, Pitch Perfect 2 and More!|date=30 January 2014|website=ComingSoon.net|access-date=9 May 2014}}</ref> The role of the protagonist, Laine Morris, was a major undertaking for Cooke, who appeared in almost every scene.<ref name=teenvogue/> The story centred around a group of friends who use the Ouija board to contact a deceased friend, but end up awakening a dark presence.<ref>{{cite web|last=Ford|first=Rebecca|title=Universal's 'Ouija' Adds 'The Fosters,' 'Red Widow' Actresses (Exclusive)|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/universals-ouija-adds-fosters-red-665187?mobile_redirect=false|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=11 December 2013|access-date=20 May 2014}}</ref> Despite being panned by critics,<ref>{{cite web|title=Ouija (2014)|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/ouija_2014/|publisher=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]}}</ref> ''Ouija'' was a box office success, grossing approximately $102.5 million worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ouija (2014)|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=ouija.htm|website=[[Box Office Mojo]]}}</ref>\n\nCooke next appeared in the comedy-drama film ''[[Me and Earl and the Dying Girl (film)|Me and Earl and the Dying Girl]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Sostek|first=Anya|title='Me and Earl and the Dying Girl' to start filming in East End|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/ae/movies/2014/06/03/Me-and-Earl-to-start-filming-in-East-End/stories/201406030026|website=[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]|access-date=21 August 2014|date=2 June 2014}}</ref> For the coming-of-age tale by [[Jesse Andrews]], who adapted the [[Me and Earl and the Dying Girl|original novel]] for the film, Cooke shaved off her hair to play the female lead who battles [[leukaemia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thewrap.com/bates-motel-star-olivia-cooke-talks-female-lead-indian-paintbrush-movie-exclusive/|title='Bates Motel' Star Olivia Cooke in Talks for Lead in 'Me and Earl and the Dying Girl' (Exclusive)|first=Jeff|last=Sneider|date=12 March 2014|website=[[TheWrap]]|access-date=9 May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Busis|first=Hillary|title='Bates Motel' actress Olivia Cooke debuts shaved head at Comic-Con|url=http://insidemovies.ew.com/2014/07/25/olivia-cooke-bald/|date=25 July 2014|website=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|access-date=21 August 2014}}</ref> The film premiered at the [[Sundance Film Festival]], where it was awarded both the Grand Jury and Audience Awards.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2015/03/me-and-earl-and-the-dying-girl-release-date-fox-searchlight-1201380726/|title=Sundance Hit 'Me And Earl And The Dying Girl' Gets Summer Release \u2013 Update|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|last=Hipes|first=Patrick|date=10 March 2015}}</ref> Also in 2015, Cooke voiced the [[Loch Ness Monster]] for an episode of ''[[Axe Cop (TV series)|Axe Cop]]'', which was co-written by her ''Me and Earl and the Dying Girl'' co-star [[Nick Offerman]].\n\nCooke played the titular character in the independent drama film ''[[Katie Says Goodbye]]'', alongside [[Jim Belushi]], [[Mireille Enos]], [[Christopher Abbott]], and [[Mary Steenburgen]]. The film revolves around Katie, a 17-year-old waitress attempting to overcome poverty and start a new life in [[San Francisco]] by resorting to prostitution.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/olivia-cooke-star-indie-drama-782941|title=Olivia Cooke to Star in Indie Drama 'Katie Says Goodbye' (Exclusive)|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|last=Kit|first=Borys|date=23 March 2015}}</ref> She next starred in the [[The Limehouse Golem|film adaptation]] of ''[[Dan Leno and the Limehouse Golem]]'', a gothic murder mystery, opposite [[Bill Nighy]] and [[Douglas Booth]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deadline.com/2015/04/alan-rickman-olivia-cooke-duncan-boothe-lionsgate-jane-goldman-limehouse-golem-1201411663/|title=Alan Rickman, Olivia Cooke And Douglas Booth To Star In 'The Limehouse Golem'|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|last=Jafaar|first=Ali|date=17 April 2015}}</ref> Both films premiered at the [[2016 Toronto International Film Festival]]. Cooke then starred in the thriller film ''[[Thoroughbreds (2017 film)|Thoroughbreds]]'', alongside [[Anya Taylor-Joy]] and [[Anton Yelchin]], which premiered at the [[2017 Sundance Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2016/04/olivia-cooke-anya-taylor-joy-anton-yelchin-thoroughbred-psychological-thriller-1201745650/|title=Olivia Cooke, Anya Taylor-Joy & Anton Yelchin Set For Thriller 'Thoroughbred'|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|first=Mike|last=Fleming Jr|date=27 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nCooke starred as Art3mis in [[Steven Spielberg]]'s science fiction adventure ''[[Ready Player One (film)|Ready Player One]]'', which was released in March 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.variety.com/2015/film/news/olivia-cooke-ready-player-one-steve-spielberg-1201591266/|title=Steven Spielberg Casts Olivia Cooke as Female Lead in 'Ready Player One'|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|last=Kroll|first=Justin|date=11 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2016/02/warner-bros-ready-player-one-spielberg-2018-star-wars-episode-viii-1201699211/|title=Warner Bros. Moves 'Ready Player One' Out Of 2017 & Away From Next 'Star Wars'|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|first=Anita|last=Busch|date=9 February 2016}}</ref> Later that year, she appeared alongside [[Oscar Isaac]], [[Olivia Wilde]] and [[Samuel L. Jackson]] in [[Dan Fogelman]]'s relationship drama film ''[[Life Itself (2018 film)|Life Itself]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/olivia-cooke-samuel-l-jackson-join-oscar-isaac-relationship-drama-life-970802|title=Olivia Cooke, Samuel L. Jackson Join Oscar Isaac in Relationship Drama 'Life Itself'|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|last=Mia|first=Galuppo|date=31 January 2017}}</ref> and played the lead character, [[Becky Sharp (character)|Becky Sharp]] in the [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] production of ''[[Vanity Fair (novel)|Vanity Fair]]''.\n\n==Personal life==\nCooke resides in [[New York City]].<ref name=diy/><ref>{{cite web|last=Mulkerrins|first=Jane|title=Olivia Cooke: 'Mysterious and quirky characters are more alluring'|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/film/me-and-earl-and-the-dying-girl/olivia-cooke-interview/|website=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=8 June 2015|access-date=1 December 2015}}</ref> In 2020, Cooke started dating actor [[Ben Hardy (actor)|Ben Hardy]].\n\nIn 2014, Cooke supported the [[Save the Children]] campaign by appearing in [[Bulgari]] advertisements.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://olivia-cooke.com/bulgari-save-the-children-campaign-launch/|title=Bulgari - Save The Children Campaign Launch|date=22 April 2014|website=Olivia Cooke Central|access-date=9 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n| style=\"background:#ffc;\"| {{dagger|alt=Films that have not been released yet}}\n| Denotes films that have not yet been released\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Year\n! scope=\"col\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\" | Role\n! scope=\"col\" | Director\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"| 2014\n! scope=\"row\" | ''Ruby's Skin''\n| Ruby\n| {{sort|Tailyour|Claire Tailyour}}\n| Short film\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''{{sort|Quiet Ones|[[The Quiet Ones (2014 film)|The Quiet Ones]]}}''\n| Jane Harper\n| {{sortname|John|Pogue}}\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''{{sort|Signal|[[The Signal (2014 film)|The Signal]]}}''\n| Haley Peterson\n| {{sortname|William|Eubank}}\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Ouija (2014 film)|Ouija]]''\n| Laine Morris\n| {{sortname|Stiles|White}}\n|\n|-\n| 2015\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Me and Earl and the Dying Girl (film)|Me and Earl and the Dying Girl]]''\n| Rachel Kushner\n| {{sortname|Alfonso|Gomez-Rejon}}\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 2016\n! scope=\"row\" | ''{{sort|Limehouse