nter;\" | <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.screendaily.com/news/screen-unveils-2014-uk-stars-of-tomorrow/5072576.article|title=Screen unveils 2014 UK Stars of Tomorrow|website=Screen Daily|date=5 June 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\"| 2015\n| [[Fangoria|Fangoria Chainsaw Awards]]\n| Best Supporting Actress\n| ''[[The Quiet Ones (2014 film)|The Quiet Ones]]''\n| {{draw|3rd Place}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fangoria.com/new/the-2015-fangoria-chainsaw-awards-winners-and-full-results/|title=The 2015 FANGORIA Chainsaw Awards Winners and Full Results!|website=[[Fangoria]]|last=Gingold|first=Michael|date=1 June 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[San Diego Film Critics Society]]\n| [[San Diego Film Critics Society Award for Best Supporting Actress|Best Supporting Actress]]\n| rowspan=\"4\"| ''[[Me and Earl and the Dying Girl (film)|Me and Earl and the Dying Girl]]''\n| {{nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sdfcs.org/2015-san-diego-film-critics-society-award-nominations/|title=2015 San Diego Film Critics Society\u2019s Award Nominations|website=[[San Diego Film Critics Society]]|date=11 December 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Women's Image Network Awards]]\n| Best Actress \u2013 Feature Film\n| {{nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thewinawards.com/17_WINAwards.html|title=The WIN Awards \u2013 Women's Image Awards 2015 Nominees|website=[[Women's Image Network Awards]]|access-date=9 December 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| Online Film & Television Association (OFTA) Awards\n| Best Breakthrough Performance - Female\n| {{nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oftaawards.com/film-awards/20th-annual-film-awards-2015/|title=20th Annual Film Awards (2015)|website=Online Film & Television Association (OFTA) Awards}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2016\n| [[Empire Awards]]\n| [[Empire Award for Best Female Newcomer|Best Female Newcomer]]\n| {{nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.empireonline.com/movies/features/2016-jameson-empire-awards/|title=The 2015 Jameson Empire Awards|website=[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]|date=18 February 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2017\n| Manchester Film Festival\n| Festival Prize \u2013 Best Actress\n| rowspan=\"2\"| ''[[Katie Says Goodbye]]''\n| {{won}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.maniff.com/news/2017/3/7/and-the-winners-are|title=The 2017 Manchester Film Festival Winners|website=Manchester Film Festival|date=7 March 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Newport Beach Film Festival]]\n| Jury Award \u2013 Best Actress\n| {{won}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newportbeachfilmfest.com/nbff-news/18th-annual-nbff-announces-award-winners/|title=The 2017 Newport Beach Film Festival Winners|website=[[Newport Beach Film Festival]]|date=28 April 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\"| 2018\n| rowspan=\"2\"| [[MTV Movie & TV Awards]]\n| [[MTV Movie Award for Best Kiss|Best Kiss]] <small>(with [[Tye Sheridan]])</small>\n| rowspan=\"4\"| ''[[Ready Player One (film)|Ready Player One]]''\n| {{nom}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lists/mtv-movie-tv-awards-2018-nominations-complete-list-1108100 |title=MTV Movie & TV Awards: 'Black Panther,' 'Stranger Things' Top Nominations |last=Nordyke |first=Kimberly |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=3 May 2018 |accessdate=3 May 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180503235147/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lists/mtv-movie-tv-awards-2018-nominations-complete-list-1108100 |archivedate=3 May 2018 }}</ref>\n|-\n| [[MTV Movie Award for Best On-Screen Duo|Best On-Screen Team]] <small>(with Tye Sheridan, Philip Zhao, [[Win Morisaki]] and [[Lena Waithe]])</small>\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| [[Teen Choice Awards]]\n| Choice Sci-Fi Movie Actress\n| {{nom}}\n|rowspan=\"2\"|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.goldderby.com/article/2018/teen-choice-awards-2018-riverdale-the-greatest-showman-shadowhunters-news-153708642/|title=\u2018Riverdale,\u2019 \u2018The Greatest Showman,\u2019 \u2018Shadowhunters\u2019 and more win big at Teen Choice Awards 2018\n|publisher=\"Fox\"|accessdate=June 25, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| Choice Breakout Movie Star\n| {{nom}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{IMDb name|4972453}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cooke, Olivia}}\n[[Category:1993 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century English actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Greater Manchester]]\n[[Category:English expatriates in the United States]]\n[[Category:English film actresses]]\n[[Category:English television actresses]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Oldham]]\n[[Category:People from Royton]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|English actress}}\n{{EngvarB|date=March 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Olivia Cooke\n| image        = Olivia Cooke by Gage Skidmore 2.jpg\n| caption      = Cooke at the 2018 [[WonderCon]]\n| birth_name   = Olivia Kate Cooke\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|1993|12|27|Age 26}}\n| birth_place  = [[Oldham]], England\n| residence    = [[New York City]], U.S.\n| occupation   = Actress\n| years_active = 2012\u2013present\n}}\n\n'''Olivia Kate Cooke'''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:QVH9-6K2H|title=Person Details for Olivia Kate Cooke, \"England and Wales Birth Registration Index, 1837\u20132008\"|website=[[FamilySearch]]|access-date=6 December 2015}}</ref> (born 27 December 1993) is an English actress. She is known for her starring role as [[List of Bates Motel characters#Emma Decody|Emma Decody]] in the [[A&E (TV channel)|A&E]] drama thriller series ''[[Bates Motel (TV series)|Bates Motel]]'' (2013\u20132017) and as [[Becky Sharp]] in the period drama [[miniseries]] ''[[Vanity Fair (2018 TV series)|Vanity Fair]]'' (2018). \n\nCooke has also starred in the horror film ''[[Ouija (2014 film)|Ouija]]'' (2014), the comedy-drama film ''[[Me and Earl and the Dying Girl (film)|Me and Earl and the Dying Girl]]'' (2015), the period horror mystery film ''[[The Limehouse Golem]]'' (2016), the thriller film ''[[Thoroughbreds (2017 film)|Thoroughbreds]]'' (2017), and the [[Steven Spielberg]]\u2013directed science fiction film ''[[Ready Player One (film)|Ready Player One]]'' (2018).\n\n==Early life==\nCooke was born and raised in [[Oldham]], [[Greater Manchester]]. Her father, John Cooke, is a retired police officer, and her mother, Lindsy (n\u00e9e Wild), is a sales representative. She has a younger sister, Eleanor.<ref name=interview>{{cite web|url=http://www.interviewmagazine.com/culture/discovery-olivia-cooke|title=Discovery: Olivia Cooke|first=Emma|last=Brown|website=[[Interview (magazine)|Interview]]|access-date=9 May 2014}}</ref><ref name=chronicle>{{cite web|url=http://www.oldham-chronicle.co.uk/news-features/8/news/75418/secrets-out-olivia-a-rising-star-in-uk-and-us|title=Secret's out: Olivia a rising star in UK and US|date=21 November 2012|website=[[Oldham Evening Chronicle]]|access-date=21 August 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140821180754/http://www.oldham-chronicle.co.uk/news-features/8/news/75418/secrets-out-olivia-a-rising-star-in-uk-and-us|archivedate=21 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oldhamathletic.co.uk/news/article/20130612-safetyofficer-861080.aspx|title=Latics' new safety officer|website=Oldham Athletic|date=12 June 2013|access-date=13 December 2015}}</ref> When Cooke was a child, her parents divorced, and she and her younger sister lived with their mother.<ref name=thestar>{{cite web|last=Barnard|first=Linda|title=Three questions for Thomas Mann, RJ Cyler, Olivia Cooke, stars of Me and Earl and the Dying Girl|url=https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/movies/2015/06/08/three-questions-for-thomas-mann-rj-cyler-olivia-cooke-stars-of-me-and-earl-and-the-dying-girl.html|date=8 June 2015|website=[[Toronto Star]]}}</ref> Cooke attended [[Royton and Crompton School|Royton and Crompton Academy]] and studied drama at [[Oldham Sixth Form College]], leaving before the end of her [[A-levels]] to appear in ''[[Blackout (TV series)|Blackout]]''.<ref name=chronicle/>\n\nAt a young age, Cooke practiced ballet and gymnastics. She started acting when she was 8 years old at an after-school drama programme in her hometown, called the [[Oldham Theatre Workshop]]. For years, Cooke performed only as part of the ensemble, until she was 17, when she starred as [[Maria (West Side Story)|Maria]] alongside Tomas Manchester in Oldham Sixth Form College's production of ''[[West Side Story]]''. Soon after, Cooke landed her first and last leading role for the Oldham Theatre Workshop, in ''Prom: The Musical'', a remake of ''[[Cinderella]]''.<ref name=interview/><ref name=chronicle/>\n\nWhen she was 14, Cooke secured her first local talent agent in [[Manchester]], who placed her in a number of commercials.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://voices.suntimes.com/arts-entertainment/the-daily-sizzle/the-quiet-ones-star-olivia-cooke-i-have-no-dignity-anymore-after-this-movie/#.U2e_FnrD8m8|title='The Quiet Ones' star Olivia Cooke: 'I have no dignity anymore after this movie.'|last=Pearlman|first=Cindy|website=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|date=23 April 2014|accessdate=9 May 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141218065158/http://voices.suntimes.com/arts-entertainment/the-daily-sizzle/the-quiet-ones-star-olivia-cooke-i-have-no-dignity-anymore-after-this-movie/#.U2e_FnrD8m8|archivedate=18 December 2014}}</ref> In 2012, she appeared in [[One Direction]]'s \"Autumn Term\" tour video, as a student getting a piggyback ride from [[Harry Styles]].<ref name=teenvogue>{{cite web|url=http://www.teenvogue.com/entertainment/movies/2014-03/olivia-cooke/?slide=1|title=Meet Olivia Cooke, the Scary-Good Actress Set to Take Hollywood by Storm|last=Rotunno|first=Anthony|website=[[Teen Vogue]]|access-date=9 May 2014}}</ref> During her audition for this bit part, Cooke entertained the producers by performing a split.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.toofab.com/2014/04/25/olivia-cooke-bates-motel-the-quiet-ones-one-direction/|title='The Quiet Ones' Star Talks Ouiji Boards, 'Bates Motel' & Riding Harry Styles!|first=Brian|last=Particelli|website=TooFab|date=25 April 2014|access-date=19 May 2014}}</ref> Although Cooke's agent discouraged her from enrolling in drama school because she was already getting acting work, Cooke was keen on applying to the [[Royal Academy of Dramatic Art]] (RADA). She made it to the final round of auditions, but was not accepted.<ref name=interview/>\n\n==Career==\n\n===2012\u20132013: Career beginnings===\nAfter Cooke performed at the Oldham Theatre Workshop, Beverley Keogh, a casting director next door to her agency, fought to get her roles in television. Cooke starred in two [[BBC]] miniseries productions in 2012: ''[[Blackout (TV series)|Blackout]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://chrisecclestonbulletin.blogspot.com/2011/05/fuse.html?m=1|title='Blackout'|website=Art Thou Beguil'd Now? Chris Eccleston Bulletin|access-date=9 May 2014}}</ref> as the daughter of [[Christopher Eccleston]]'s character, and ''[[The Secret of Crickley Hall (TV series)|The Secret of Crickley Hall]]'', as a young teacher at a tyrannical orphanage in the 1940s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/news/a407099/psycho-tv-prequel-bates-motel-adds-blackout-star-olivia-cooke.html|title='Psycho' TV prequel 'Bates Motel' adds 'Blackout' star Olivia Cooke|last=Jeffery|first=Morgan|website=[[Digital Spy]]|date=20 September 2012|access-date=30 September 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aetv.com/bates-motel/cast/olivia-cooke|title=Meet the Cast: Olivia Cooke as Emma Decody|website=[[Bates Motel (TV series)|Bates Motel]]. AETV.com|access-date=9 May 2014}}</ref> Cooke stated that she felt better suited for television than theatre, as she was embarrassed by the exaggerated gestures sometimes required for stage acting.<ref name=interview/> Despite being a novice, Cooke distinguished herself among European actresses in the gruelling casting process for ''[[The Quiet Ones (2014 film)|The Quiet Ones]]'', which opened in April 2014, two years after filming took place.<ref name=diy>{{cite web|url=http://www.thisisfakediy.co.uk/mobile/articles/film/interview-olivia-cooke/|title=Interview: Olivia Cooke|date=9 April 2014|website=[[This Is Fake DIY|DIY]] Film|access-date=9 May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The Quiet Ones World Premiere|url=http://www.thelondonfilmreview.com/even/quiet-ones-world-premiere/|website=The London Film Review|access-date=22 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, following ''The Quiet Ones'', Cooke acquired an agent in [[Los Angeles]].<ref name=collider/> After reading the character descriptions for [[A&E (TV channel)|A&E]]'s contemporary ''[[Psycho (1960 film)|Psycho]]'' prequel ''[[Bates Motel (TV series)|Bates Motel]]'', she sent an audition tape for the role of Emma Decody.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://zap2it.com/blogs/bates_motels_olivia_cooke_im_not_sexy_so_ill_go_for_emma-2013-04|title='Bates Motel's' Olivia Cooke: 'I'm not sexy, so I'll go for Emma'|last=O'Hare|first=Kate|website=[[Zap2It]]|date=8 April 2013|access-date=30 September 2013}}</ref> Three weeks later, Cooke earned the part of Emma, her first American role.<ref name=collider>{{cite web|url=http://www.collider.com/nicola-peltz-olivia-cooke-bates-motel-interview/|title=Nicola Peltz and Olivia Cooke Talk BATES MOTEL, Their Characters, Their Familiarity with PSYCHO, and More|last=Radish|first=Christina|website=[[Collider (website)|Collider]]|access-date=30 September 2013}}</ref> She was originally disappointed when the producers made Emma [[Manchester|Mancunian]], believing it was a fail-safe measure regarding her accent. However, aided by fellow English actor [[Freddie Highmore]], who has previous experience with an American accent, Cooke has since been mistaken to be American.<ref name=interview/><ref>{{cite web|title=Bates Motel: Olivia Cooke Is Not American|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UqBFjXN9-mY|website=[[A&E (TV channel)|A&E]]. [[YouTube]]|date=7 May 2014|access-date=22 May 2014}}</ref> Cooke also contributed short videos for Emma's fictitious [[blog]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aetv.com/bates-motel/emmas-blog/|title=Emma's Blog: My Life in Fast-Forward|website=[[Bates Motel (TV series)|Bates Motel]]. AETV.com|access-date=9 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n===2014\u2013present: Further success===\n[[File:Olivia Cooke SDCC2017.jpg|thumb|upright|Cooke speaking at the 2017 [[San Diego Comic-Con]]]]\nCooke's second feature film ''[[The Signal (2014 film)|The Signal]]'', with [[Brenton Thwaites]] and [[Laurence Fishburne]], opened at the [[2014 Sundance Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Sundance 2014: Park City at Midnight|url=http://www.indiewire.com/article/sundance-2014-park-city-at-midnight|website=[[Indiewire]]|date=10 January 2014}}</ref> Cooke starred as Haley Peterson, an American [[MIT]] student transferring to [[Caltech]], who encounters strange occurrences as she, her boyfriend, and her best friend are lured into the desert by a hacker. In October 2014, Cooke led the cast of ''[[Ouija (2014 film)|Ouija]]'', a horror film based on [[Hasbro]]'s board game.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.comingsoon.net/news/movienews.php?id=114202|title=Universal Dates Crimson Peak, Ouija, Pitch Perfect 2 and More!|date=30 January 2014|website=ComingSoon.net|access-date=9 May 2014}}</ref> The role of the protagonist, Laine Morris, was a major undertaking for Cooke, who appeared in almost every scene.<ref name=teenvogue/> The story centred around a group of friends who use the Ouija board to contact a deceased friend, but end up awakening a dark presence.<ref>{{cite web|last=Ford|first=Rebecca|title=Universal's 'Ouija' Adds 'The Fosters,' 'Red Widow' Actresses (Exclusive)|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/universals-ouija-adds-fosters-red-665187?mobile_redirect=false|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=11 December 2013|access-date=20 May 2014}}</ref> Despite being panned by critics,<ref>{{cite web|title=Ouija (2014)|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/ouija_2014/|publisher=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]}}</ref> ''Ouija'' was a box office success, grossing approximately $102.5 million worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ouija (2014)|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=ouija.htm|website=[[Box Office Mojo]]}}</ref>\n\nCooke next appeared in the comedy-drama film ''[[Me and Earl and the Dying Girl (film)|Me and Earl and the Dying Girl]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Sostek|first=Anya|title='Me and Earl and the Dying Girl' to start filming in East End|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/ae/movies/2014/06/03/Me-and-Earl-to-start-filming-in-East-End/stories/201406030026|website=[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]|access-date=21 August 2014|date=2 June 2014}}</ref> For the coming-of-age tale by [[Jesse Andrews]], who adapted the [[Me and Earl and the Dying Girl|original novel]] for the film, Cooke shaved off her hair to play the female lead who battles [[leukaemia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thewrap.com/bates-motel-star-olivia-cooke-talks-female-lead-indian-paintbrush-movie-exclusive/|title='Bates Motel' Star Olivia Cooke in Talks for Lead in 'Me and Earl and the Dying Girl' (Exclusive)|first=Jeff|last=Sneider|date=12 March 2014|website=[[TheWrap]]|access-date=9 May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Busis|first=Hillary|title='Bates Motel' actress Olivia Cooke debuts shaved head at Comic-Con|url=http://insidemovies.ew.com/2014/07/25/olivia-cooke-bald/|date=25 July 2014|website=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|access-date=21 August 2014}}</ref> The film premiered at the [[Sundance Film Festival]], where it was awarded both the Grand Jury and Audience Awards.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2015/03/me-and-earl-and-the-dying-girl-release-date-fox-searchlight-1201380726/|title=Sundance Hit 'Me And Earl And The Dying Girl' Gets Summer Release \u2013 Update|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|last=Hipes|first=Patrick|date=10 March 2015}}</ref> Also in 2015, Cooke voiced the [[Loch Ness Monster]] for an episode of ''[[Axe Cop (TV series)|Axe Cop]]'', which was co-written by her ''Me and Earl and the Dying Girl'' co-star [[Nick Offerman]].\n\nCooke played the titular character in the independent drama film ''[[Katie Says Goodbye]]'', alongside [[Jim Belushi]], [[Mireille Enos]], [[Christopher Abbott]], and [[Mary Steenburgen]]. The film revolves around Katie, a 17-year-old waitress attempting to overcome poverty and start a new life in [[San Francisco]] by resorting to prostitution.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/olivia-cooke-star-indie-drama-782941|title=Olivia Cooke to Star in Indie Drama 'Katie Says Goodbye' (Exclusive)|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|last=Kit|first=Borys|date=23 March 2015}}</ref> She next starred in the [[The Limehouse Golem|film adaptation]] of ''[[Dan Leno and the Limehouse Golem]]'', a gothic murder mystery, opposite [[Bill Nighy]] and [[Douglas Booth]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deadline.com/2015/04/alan-rickman-olivia-cooke-duncan-boothe-lionsgate-jane-goldman-limehouse-golem-1201411663/|title=Alan Rickman, Olivia Cooke And Douglas Booth To Star In 'The Limehouse Golem'|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|last=Jafaar|first=Ali|date=17 April 2015}}</ref> Both films premiered at the [[2016 Toronto International Film Festival]]. Cooke then starred in the thriller film ''[[Thoroughbreds (2017 film)|Thoroughbreds]]'', alongside [[Anya Taylor-Joy]] and [[Anton Yelchin]], which premiered at the [[2017 Sundance Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2016/04/olivia-cooke-anya-taylor-joy-anton-yelchin-thoroughbred-psychological-thriller-1201745650/|title=Olivia Cooke, Anya Taylor-Joy & Anton Yelchin Set For Thriller 'Thoroughbred'|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|first=Mike|last=Fleming Jr|date=27 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nCooke starred as Art3mis in [[Steven Spielberg]]'s science fiction adventure ''[[Ready Player One (film)|Ready Player One]]'', which was released in March 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.variety.com/2015/film/news/olivia-cooke-ready-player-one-steve-spielberg-1201591266/|title=Steven Spielberg Casts Olivia Cooke as Female Lead in 'Ready Player One'|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|last=Kroll|first=Justin|date=11 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2016/02/warner-bros-ready-player-one-spielberg-2018-star-wars-episode-viii-1201699211/|title=Warner Bros. Moves 'Ready Player One' Out Of 2017 & Away From Next 'Star Wars'|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|first=Anita|last=Busch|date=9 February 2016}}</ref> Later that year, she appeared alongside [[Oscar Isaac]], [[Olivia Wilde]] and [[Samuel L. Jackson]] in [[Dan Fogelman]]'s relationship drama film ''[[Life Itself (2018 film)|Life Itself]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/olivia-cooke-samuel-l-jackson-join-oscar-isaac-relationship-drama-life-970802|title=Olivia Cooke, Samuel L. Jackson Join Oscar Isaac in Relationship Drama 'Life Itself'|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|last=Mia|first=Galuppo|date=31 January 2017}}</ref> and played the lead character, [[Becky Sharp (character)|Becky Sharp]] in the [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] production of ''[[Vanity Fair (novel)|Vanity Fair]]''.\n\n==Personal life==\nCooke resides in [[New York City]].<ref name=diy/><ref>{{cite web|last=Mulkerrins|first=Jane|title=Olivia Cooke: 'Mysterious and quirky characters are more alluring'|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/film/me-and-earl-and-the-dying-girl/olivia-cooke-interview/|website=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=8 June 2015|access-date=1 December 2015}}</ref> Cooke is close friends with her ''Me and Earl and the Dying Girl'' co-star [[Thomas Mann (actor)|Thomas Mann]],<ref name=thestar/> and her ''Bates Motel'' co-stars [[Freddie Highmore]] and [[Nicola Peltz]].<ref name=collider/>In 2020, Cooke started dating actor [[Ben Hardy (actor)|Ben Hardy]]\n\nIn 2014, Cooke supported the [[Save the Children]] campaign by appearing in [[Bulgari]] advertisements.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://olivia-cooke.com/bulgari-save-the-children-campaign-launch/|title=Bulgari - Save The Children Campaign Launch|date=22 April 2014|website=Olivia Cooke Central|access-date=9 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n| style=\"background:#ffc;\"| {{dagger|alt=Films that have not been released yet}}\n| Denotes films that have not yet been released\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Year\n! scope=\"col\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\" | Role\n! scope=\"col\" | Director\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"| 2014\n! scope=\"row\" | ''Ruby's Skin''\n| Ruby\n| {{sort|Tailyour|Claire Tailyour}}\n| Short film\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''{{sort|Quiet Ones|[[The Quiet Ones (2014 film)|The Quiet Ones]]}}''\n| Jane Harper\n| {{sortname|John|Pogue}}\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''{{sort|Signal|[[The Signal (2014 film)|The Signal]]}}''\n| Haley Peterson\n| {{sortname|William|Eubank}}\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Ouija (2014 film)|Ouija]]''\n| Laine Morris\n| {{sortname|Stiles|White}}\n|\n|-\n| 2015\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Me and Earl and the Dying Girl (film)|Me and Earl and the Dying Girl]]''\n| Rachel Kushner\n| {{sortname|Alfonso|Gomez-Rejon}}\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 2016\n! scope=\"row\" | ''{{sort|Limehouse Golem|[[The Limehouse Golem]]}}''\n| Lizzie Cree\n| {{sort|Carlos Medina|Juan Carlos Medina}}\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Katie Says Goodbye]]''\n| Katie\n| {{sort|Roberts|Wayne Roberts}}\n| \n|-\n| 2017\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Thoroughbreds (2017 film)|Thoroughbreds]]''\n| Amanda\n| {{sortname|Cory|Finley}}\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"| 2018\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Ready Player One (film)|Ready Player One]]''\n| Samantha Cook / Art3mis\n| {{sortname|Steven|Spielberg}}\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''Follow the Roses''\n| Angie\n| {{sort|Steele|Jen Steele}}\n| Short film\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Life Itself (2018 film)|Life Itself]]''\n| Dylan Dempsey \n| {{sortname|Dan|Fogelman}}\n| \n|-\n| 2019\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Sound of Metal]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/riz-ahmed-olivia-cooke-sound-of-metal-1202879738/|title=Riz Ahmed and Olivia Cooke to Star in Music Drama \u2018Sound of Metal\u2019|first=Justin|last=Kroll|date=20 July 2018|work=Variety}}</ref>\n| Lou\n| {{sort|Marder|Darius Marder}}\n| \n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"| 2020\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"background:#ffc;\"| ''[[Little Fish (2020 film)|Little Fish]]''{{dagger}}\n| Emma\n| {{sort|Hartigan|Chad Hartigan}}\n| Post-production\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"background:#ffc;\"| ''[[Naked Singularity (film)|Naked Singularity]]''{{dagger}}<ref>[https://deadline.com/2019/04/olivia-cooke-john-boyega-scott-free-naked-singularity-1202591129/ Olivia Cooke Joins John Boyega In Scott Free\u2019s \u2018Naked Singularity\u2019]</ref>\n| Lea\n|Chase Palmer\n|Post-production<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www1.nyc.gov/assets/mome/pdf/reeljobs.pdf|title=After Yang|website=NYC Media & Production|accessdate=30 April 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"background:#ffc;\"| ''[[Pixie (film)|Pixie]]''{{dagger}}\n| Pixie\n| {{sortname|Barnaby|Thompson}}\n| Post-production\n|-\n|}<!--do NOT add films that are in pre-production, in development or announced per [[WP:CRYSTAL]]-->\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n| style=\"background:#ffc;\"| {{dagger|alt=Series that have not been released yet}}\n| Denotes series that have not yet been released\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Year\n! scope=\"col\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\" | Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 2012\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Blackout (TV series)|Blackout]]''\n| Meg Demoys\n| 3 episode