{"title_page": "USS Stiletto (1885)", "text_new": "{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=Stiletto (wooden torpedo boat). Starboard side, 1891 - NARA - 512900.tif\n|Ship caption=''Stiletto'' in 1891\n}}\n{{Infobox Ship Career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship country=United States\n|Ship flag={{USN flag|1911}}\n|Ship name=\n|Ship namesake=\n|Ship ordered=\n|Ship builder=[[Herreshoff Manufacturing Co.]]\n|Ship laid down=1885\n|Ship launched=\n|Ship acquired=3 March 1887\n|Ship commissioned=\n|Ship decommissioned=\n|Ship in service=July 1887\n|Ship out of service=\n|Ship struck=27 January 1911\n|Ship reinstated=\n|Ship honours=\n|Ship fate=Sold for scrap 18 July 1911\n|Ship status=\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=\n|Ship class=\n|Ship displacement=31 tons\n|Ship length=94'\n|Ship beam=11' 6\"\n|Ship draught=\n|Ship draft=5'\n|Ship propulsion=\n|Ship speed=18.2 knots\n|Ship range=\n|Ship complement=6\n|Ship sensors=\n|Ship EW=\n|Ship armament=\n|Ship armour=\n|Ship armor=\n|Ship aircraft=\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n\n'''USS Stiletto''', a wooden [[torpedo boat]], was launched in 1885 at the [[Herreshoff Manufacturing Co.]], [[Bristol, Rhode Island]], as a private speculation. She was purchased for the [[United States Navy]] under an Act of Congress dated 3 March 1887, and entered service in July 1887, attached to the  [[Naval Torpedo Station]] in [[Newport Rhode Island]].\n\n''Stiletto'' was the Navy's first torpedo boat capable of launching self-propelled [[torpedo]]es. Purchased for experimental evaluation, ''Stiletto'' was based throughout her career at Newport and often captained by Andrew Wright. During 1897, she was modified to burn fuel oil, but results of [[sea trial]]s held subsequently were disappointing, and the experiment was not repeated. On 14 July 1897 she fouled steam [[Yacht]]  \"Nautilus\"  ({{flag|United States|1896}})  at [[Bristol, Connecticut]] doing minor damage to the Yacht.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=osu.32435066693086&view=1up&seq=40 |page=40\u20146 |title=Annual report of the Supervising Inspector-general Steamboat-inspection Service, Year ending June 30, 1898 |location=Washington |publisher=Government Printing Office |date=1898|via=Haithi Trust |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref> ''Stiletto'' was struck from the [[Naval Vessel Register|Navy list]] on 27 January 1911 and sold on 18 July 1911 at Newport to James F. Nolan of [[East Boston, Massachusetts]] for [[scrap]]ping.\n\n{{Gallery\n |title=Various states of ''Stiletto''\n |align=center\n |File:Stiletto plans-IMG 5919.JPG|Construction plan\n |File:Stiletto plans-IMG 5921.JPG|Engine plan\n |File:Model of Stiletto 1885 at MIT-IMG 5917-white.jpg|model of \"Stiletto\" (1885) at MIT, made by Pat Bianco in 1996, on loan from the Naval War College Museum\n |File:Stebbins-49-Stiletto.jpg|''Stiletto'' in 1887\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n*{{DANFS|http://www.history.navy.mil/research/histories/ship-histories/danfs/s/stiletto.html}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{commonscat-inline|Stiletto (ship, 1887)|Stiletto}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stiletto}}\n[[Category:Torpedo boats of the United States Navy]]\n", "text_old": "{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=Stiletto (wooden torpedo boat). Starboard side, 1891 - NARA - 512900.tif\n|Ship caption=''Stiletto'' in 1891\n}}\n{{Infobox Ship Career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship country=United States\n|Ship flag={{USN flag|1911}}\n|Ship name=\n|Ship namesake=\n|Ship ordered=\n|Ship builder=[[Herreshoff Manufacturing Co.]]\n|Ship laid down=1885\n|Ship launched=\n|Ship acquired=3 March 1887\n|Ship commissioned=\n|Ship decommissioned=\n|Ship in service=July 1887\n|Ship out of service=\n|Ship struck=27 January 1911\n|Ship reinstated=\n|Ship honours=\n|Ship fate=Sold for scrap 18 July 1911\n|Ship status=\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=\n|Ship class=\n|Ship displacement=31 tons\n|Ship length=94'\n|Ship beam=11' 6\"\n|Ship draught=\n|Ship draft=5'\n|Ship propulsion=\n|Ship speed=18.2 knots\n|Ship range=\n|Ship complement=6\n|Ship sensors=\n|Ship EW=\n|Ship armament=\n|Ship armour=\n|Ship armor=\n|Ship aircraft=\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n\n'''USS Stiletto''', a wooden [[torpedo boat]], was launched in 1885 at the [[Herreshoff Manufacturing Co.]], [[Bristol, Rhode Island]], as a private speculation. She was purchased for the [[United States Navy]] under an Act of Congress dated 3 March 1887, and entered service in July 1887, attached to the  [[Naval Torpedo Station]] in [[Newport Rhode Island]].\n\n''Stiletto'' was the Navy's first torpedo boat capable of launching self-propelled [[torpedo]]es. Purchased for experimental evaluation, ''Stiletto'' was based throughout her career at Newport and often captained by Andrew Wright. During 1897, she was modified to burn fuel oil, but results of [[sea trial]]s held subsequently were disappointing, and the experiment was not repeated. On 14 July 1897 she fouled steam [[Yacht]]  \"Nautilus\"  ({{flag|United States|1896}})  at [[Bristol, Connecticut]] doing minor damage to the Yacht.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=osu.32435066693086&view=1up&seq=40 |page=40\u20146 |title=Annual report of the Supervising Inspector-general Steamboat-inspection Service, Year ending June 30, 1898 |location=Washington |publisher=Government Printing Office |date=1898|via=Haithi Trust |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref> ''Stiletto'' was struck from the [[Naval Vessel Register|Navy list]] on 27 January 1911 and sold on 18 July 1911 at Newport to James F. Nolan of [[East Boston, Massachusetts]] for [[scrap]]ping.\n\n{{Gallery\n |title=Various states of ''Stiletto''\n |align=center\n |File:Stiletto plans-IMG 5919.JPG|Constrution plan\n |File:Stiletto plans-IMG 5921.JPG|Engine plan\n |File:Model of Stiletto 1885 at MIT-IMG 5917-white.jpg|model of \"Stiletto\" (1885) at MIT, made by Pat Bianco in 1996, on loan from the Naval War College Museum\n |File:Stebbins-49-Stiletto.jpg|''Stiletto'' in 1887\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n*{{DANFS|http://www.history.navy.mil/research/histories/ship-histories/danfs/s/stiletto.html}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{commonscat-inline|Stiletto (ship, 1887)|Stiletto}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stiletto}}\n[[Category:Torpedo boats of the United States Navy]]\n", "name_user": "Rama", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/USS_Stiletto_(1885)"}
